WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.479 align:middle line:90%
[SQUEAKING]

00:00:01.479 --> 00:00:02.465 align:middle line:90%


00:00:02.465 --> 00:00:03.451 align:middle line:90%
[RUSTLING]

00:00:03.451 --> 00:00:04.437 align:middle line:90%


00:00:04.437 --> 00:00:05.423 align:middle line:90%
[CLICKING]

00:00:05.423 --> 00:00:11.178 align:middle line:90%


00:00:11.178 --> 00:00:11.970 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: OK.

00:00:11.970 --> 00:00:16.140 align:middle line:84%
So last time, we talked
about at towards the end,

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:17.496 align:middle line:90%
we talked about sequences.

00:00:17.496 --> 00:00:21.290 align:middle line:90%


00:00:21.290 --> 00:00:25.610 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular, we
talked about square root of 2

00:00:25.610 --> 00:00:27.740 align:middle line:90%
by 2 square root of 2.

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:30.890 align:middle line:84%
We could think about
this if we wanted

00:00:30.890 --> 00:00:34.710 align:middle line:84%
to think about the square
root of 2 on the real line.

00:00:34.710 --> 00:00:39.170 align:middle line:84%
Then we have here
1 and we have two.

00:00:39.170 --> 00:00:44.780 align:middle line:84%
And we could define a sequence
of numbers where the first one

00:00:44.780 --> 00:00:55.260 align:middle line:84%
is 1, the second one is
1.4, the third is a 1.4.1,

00:00:55.260 --> 00:01:00.650 align:middle line:84%
and the next one is then the
next digit in square root of 2,

00:01:00.650 --> 00:01:06.880 align:middle line:90%
so 1.4.1.4, et cetera.

00:01:06.880 --> 00:01:14.890 align:middle line:84%
And so this is like a sequence
of numbers that are increasing.

00:01:14.890 --> 00:01:18.160 align:middle line:84%
And it is square root
of 2 where you're

00:01:18.160 --> 00:01:20.270 align:middle line:90%
taking more and more digits.

00:01:20.270 --> 00:01:26.710 align:middle line:84%
So square root of 2
is, in some sense,

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:32.910 align:middle line:90%
the limit of the sequence.

00:01:32.910 --> 00:01:38.800 align:middle line:90%


00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:43.123 align:middle line:84%
And so precisely,
a sequence is--

00:01:43.123 --> 00:01:44.540 align:middle line:84%
so we talked about
that last time.

00:01:44.540 --> 00:01:47.060 align:middle line:84%
But let me just remind
you what that is.

00:01:47.060 --> 00:02:01.830 align:middle line:84%
So a sequence is a function
from the natural numbers--

00:02:01.830 --> 00:02:07.250 align:middle line:84%
so f goes from the natural
numbers into the real.

00:02:07.250 --> 00:02:12.260 align:middle line:84%
And the value at some
natural number n--

00:02:12.260 --> 00:02:15.830 align:middle line:84%
the value of this function
at a natural number n.

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:19.670 align:middle line:84%
This we denote-- usually,
it's a standard notation

00:02:19.670 --> 00:02:24.170 align:middle line:84%
that one denoted like this
where the n is a subscript.

00:02:24.170 --> 00:02:24.670 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:02:24.670 --> 00:02:28.160 align:middle line:90%


00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:33.540 align:middle line:84%
And so let's take a look at a
couple of different sequences.

00:02:33.540 --> 00:02:37.160 align:middle line:84%
So we talked-- so this
here really is a sequence.

00:02:37.160 --> 00:02:46.310 align:middle line:84%
Another example is where you
have a n equal to minus 1

00:02:46.310 --> 00:02:48.740 align:middle line:90%
to the power n.

00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:52.740 align:middle line:84%
So n again is this
natural number.

00:02:52.740 --> 00:02:57.580 align:middle line:84%
So this means that this
sequence a1 is equal to minus 1,

00:02:57.580 --> 00:03:02.740 align:middle line:84%
a2 is equal to minus 1 times
minus 1, so that's one.

00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:10.460 align:middle line:84%
a3 is minus 1 times
minus 1 times minus 1.

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:13.220 align:middle line:90%
So this is minus 1.

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:20.620 align:middle line:84%
And a4 is minus 1 multiplied
itself four 4 So that's 1.

00:03:20.620 --> 00:03:21.200 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:03:21.200 --> 00:03:34.240 align:middle line:84%
So this sequence here, it's
alternating between the values

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:37.630 align:middle line:90%
minus 1 and 1.

00:03:37.630 --> 00:03:40.490 align:middle line:90%
So it's starting off at minus 1.

00:03:40.490 --> 00:03:41.960 align:middle line:90%
And then it goes to 1.

00:03:41.960 --> 00:03:46.570 align:middle line:84%
Then it goes to minus 1,
1, minus 1, et cetera.

00:03:46.570 --> 00:03:47.941 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:03:47.941 --> 00:03:53.060 align:middle line:84%
And so this sequence here,
right, it doesn't really--

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:56.420 align:middle line:84%
it's not-- it doesn't
really convert.

00:03:56.420 --> 00:03:58.770 align:middle line:84%
It's not-- it doesn't
really have a limit.

00:03:58.770 --> 00:04:02.040 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- we'll make
this precise in just a minute.

00:04:02.040 --> 00:04:04.285 align:middle line:84%
So this sequence does
not have a limit.

00:04:04.285 --> 00:04:13.670 align:middle line:90%


00:04:13.670 --> 00:04:19.850 align:middle line:84%
Another an example of a
sequence is a decaying sequence

00:04:19.850 --> 00:04:20.519 align:middle line:90%
like this.

00:04:20.519 --> 00:04:25.760 align:middle line:90%
So a n is equal to 1 over n.

00:04:25.760 --> 00:04:34.460 align:middle line:84%
So a1 is equal to 1, a2 is equal
to 1/2, a3 is equal to 1/2,

00:04:34.460 --> 00:04:38.070 align:middle line:90%
and then a4 is equal to 1/4.

00:04:38.070 --> 00:04:41.000 align:middle line:84%
So these numbers here
are all positive.

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:41.520 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:04:41.520 --> 00:04:45.480 align:middle line:84%
The values of a is all-- all
of them are all positive.

00:04:45.480 --> 00:04:49.820 align:middle line:84%
And they become
smaller and smaller.

00:04:49.820 --> 00:04:53.350 align:middle line:84%
So you could write
that suggestively.

00:04:53.350 --> 00:04:57.190 align:middle line:84%
This here is going
down like that.

00:04:57.190 --> 00:05:03.940 align:middle line:84%
And so it seems obvious
that this limit here--

00:05:03.940 --> 00:05:06.050 align:middle line:90%
that this sequence has a limit.

00:05:06.050 --> 00:05:07.155 align:middle line:90%
This here has a limit.

00:05:07.155 --> 00:05:10.960 align:middle line:90%


00:05:10.960 --> 00:05:13.590 align:middle line:90%
And the limit is 0.

00:05:13.590 --> 00:05:20.530 align:middle line:90%


00:05:20.530 --> 00:05:25.280 align:middle line:84%
So now let me make
the formal definition.

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:30.880 align:middle line:84%
So what does it mean that
a sequence is convergent?

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:33.120 align:middle line:90%
So a sequence.

00:05:33.120 --> 00:05:37.930 align:middle line:90%


00:05:37.930 --> 00:05:48.530 align:middle line:90%
a n is convergent to a.

00:05:48.530 --> 00:05:50.515 align:middle line:90%
So a is another real number.

00:05:50.515 --> 00:05:53.330 align:middle line:90%


00:05:53.330 --> 00:05:59.630 align:middle line:84%
A sequence a n is convergent to
a if the following is the case--

00:05:59.630 --> 00:06:01.045 align:middle line:90%
if the following holds.

00:06:01.045 --> 00:06:10.220 align:middle line:90%


00:06:10.220 --> 00:06:24.170 align:middle line:84%
For all epsilon-- for all
epsilon greater than 0,

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:31.550 align:middle line:84%
there exists a
natural number such

00:06:31.550 --> 00:06:42.170 align:middle line:84%
that if little n is bigger
than this natural number,

00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:48.500 align:middle line:84%
then the difference between
a n and the supposed limit

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:52.810 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by epsilon.

00:06:52.810 --> 00:06:58.210 align:middle line:84%
So if you think about it--
so if you think about it,

00:06:58.210 --> 00:07:01.920 align:middle line:84%
here you have on the real
line here you have a.

00:07:01.920 --> 00:07:06.940 align:middle line:84%
And so if you give
me an epsilon,

00:07:06.940 --> 00:07:09.010 align:middle line:90%
so then I'm looking at a here.

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:11.990 align:middle line:84%
I'm looking at an
interval around a.

00:07:11.990 --> 00:07:16.420 align:middle line:84%
So this is an interval
here from a minus

00:07:16.420 --> 00:07:20.320 align:middle line:90%
epsilon to a plus epsilon.

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:23.230 align:middle line:84%
And the claim is
that the sequence a n

00:07:23.230 --> 00:07:28.180 align:middle line:84%
is converging to
a if there exists

00:07:28.180 --> 00:07:33.680 align:middle line:84%
some n so that if little n is
larger than this capital N,

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:38.350 align:middle line:84%
then all of these a n
lands somewhere here.

00:07:38.350 --> 00:07:46.630 align:middle line:84%
All of them a n is in this
little interval for little n

00:07:46.630 --> 00:07:49.140 align:middle line:84%
bigger than this
capital N. Right?

00:07:49.140 --> 00:07:52.340 align:middle line:84%
That's what it means
to be convergent.

00:07:52.340 --> 00:07:54.600 align:middle line:90%
But it's like for all epsilon.

00:07:54.600 --> 00:07:59.790 align:middle line:84%
So you allow to-- someone else
is allowed to pick the epsilon.

00:07:59.790 --> 00:08:03.620 align:middle line:84%
And then you have to prove that
there exists a capital N so

00:08:03.620 --> 00:08:07.370 align:middle line:84%
that from there on and
out, all of the a n

00:08:07.370 --> 00:08:11.480 align:middle line:90%
lie in this little interval.

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:16.380 align:middle line:84%
So this is what it means for
a sequence to be convergent.

00:08:16.380 --> 00:08:23.370 align:middle line:84%
So we say that a n is convergent
to a if this is the case.

00:08:23.370 --> 00:08:26.030 align:middle line:90%
And in that case--

00:08:26.030 --> 00:08:34.789 align:middle line:84%
in that case, one also
writes that the limit

00:08:34.789 --> 00:08:39.459 align:middle line:84%
as n goes to infinity
of a n is equal to a.

00:08:39.459 --> 00:08:46.070 align:middle line:90%


00:08:46.070 --> 00:09:00.876 align:middle line:84%
So if you have a sequence a
sequence that is not convergent,

00:09:00.876 --> 00:09:02.990 align:middle line:90%
it is said to be divergent.

00:09:02.990 --> 00:09:12.735 align:middle line:90%


00:09:12.735 --> 00:09:19.960 align:middle line:84%
And so now let me
look at an example.

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:30.890 align:middle line:84%
So suppose you're looking at
the number 0.99999, et cetera.

00:09:30.890 --> 00:09:35.260 align:middle line:84%
This number here,
this is really--

00:09:35.260 --> 00:09:40.120 align:middle line:84%
this number here, we will think
about this number here as 1.

00:09:40.120 --> 00:09:44.550 align:middle line:84%
This is
indistinguishable from 1.

00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:46.980 align:middle line:84%
And in fact, what
you really think

00:09:46.980 --> 00:09:53.790 align:middle line:84%
about is that you think about
that you have a sequence where

00:09:53.790 --> 00:10:08.400 align:middle line:84%
a1 is 0.9, a2 is
0.99, a3 is 0.999,

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:15.040 align:middle line:84%
a4 is equal to
0.9999, et cetera.

00:10:15.040 --> 00:10:25.955 align:middle line:84%
So a n is where you have zero
point and then 9 n times.

00:10:25.955 --> 00:10:31.260 align:middle line:90%


00:10:31.260 --> 00:10:36.840 align:middle line:84%
If you're looking at
that sequence here,

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:43.330 align:middle line:84%
then you have that this
sequence a n is convergent to 1.

00:10:43.330 --> 00:10:50.240 align:middle line:84%
And a n-- this is one also that
is convergent to 1 like this.

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:57.810 align:middle line:90%
So a n is convergent to 1.

00:10:57.810 --> 00:10:58.310 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:10:58.310 --> 00:11:01.160 align:middle line:84%
So there's various ways of
writing that it's convergent.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.770 align:middle line:90%
You can write it like this.

00:11:03.770 --> 00:11:05.630 align:middle line:90%
This means that it's convergent.

00:11:05.630 --> 00:11:07.190 align:middle line:90%
And the limit is a.

00:11:07.190 --> 00:11:08.720 align:middle line:90%
You can write it like this.

00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:13.010 align:middle line:84%
This means that this sequence is
convergent and the limit is 1.

00:11:13.010 --> 00:11:15.165 align:middle line:84%
Or you can write
it out in words.

00:11:15.165 --> 00:11:20.800 align:middle line:90%


00:11:20.800 --> 00:11:24.220 align:middle line:84%
So this sequence-- I claim
that this sequence here

00:11:24.220 --> 00:11:25.700 align:middle line:90%
defined like this.

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:28.990 align:middle line:84%
And this is really how
you think about this.

00:11:28.990 --> 00:11:30.470 align:middle line:84%
When you think
about this number,

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:37.640 align:middle line:84%
you think about it that this is
0.99 with more and more numbers,

00:11:37.640 --> 00:11:40.480 align:middle line:84%
nines, added and
the limits, which

00:11:40.480 --> 00:11:44.520 align:middle line:84%
is really what this number
here in itself is is 1.

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:48.540 align:middle line:84%
Now let me explain why
the sequence defined

00:11:48.540 --> 00:11:53.255 align:middle line:84%
this way, why this is
convergent as a limit 1.

00:11:53.255 --> 00:12:02.730 align:middle line:90%


00:12:02.730 --> 00:12:07.840 align:middle line:84%
So now, of course, now
you give me an epsilon.

00:12:07.840 --> 00:12:13.530 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon given
epsilon greater than 0,

00:12:13.530 --> 00:12:18.000 align:middle line:84%
then I need to find a
capital N So that from there

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:21.970 align:middle line:84%
on and out the An
a n within epsilon.

00:12:21.970 --> 00:12:23.255 align:middle line:90%
So we need to find--

00:12:23.255 --> 00:12:26.700 align:middle line:90%


00:12:26.700 --> 00:12:31.620 align:middle line:84%
for this epsilon, we
need to find capital N

00:12:31.620 --> 00:12:35.020 align:middle line:84%
so that if little n is
bigger than this capital N,

00:12:35.020 --> 00:12:40.270 align:middle line:84%
then a n minus 1 is
less than epsilon.

00:12:40.270 --> 00:12:42.100 align:middle line:90%
That's what we need to do.

00:12:42.100 --> 00:12:43.960 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:12:43.960 --> 00:12:51.100 align:middle line:84%
But for your epsilon,
so to do that,

00:12:51.100 --> 00:12:54.400 align:middle line:84%
we need to choose
this capital N.

00:12:54.400 --> 00:12:57.640 align:middle line:90%
So I'm just choosing--

00:12:57.640 --> 00:13:00.310 align:middle line:84%
I just choose
capital N. So to do

00:13:00.310 --> 00:13:16.660 align:middle line:84%
that, choose capital N such that
1 over n is less than epsilon.

00:13:16.660 --> 00:13:17.530 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:13:17.530 --> 00:13:21.260 align:middle line:84%
We can do this by the
Archimedean property.

00:13:21.260 --> 00:13:37.870 align:middle line:84%
So this is-- so we can
find such an m and capital

00:13:37.870 --> 00:13:43.160 align:middle line:84%
N by the Archimedean property
that we discussed last time.

00:13:43.160 --> 00:13:48.990 align:middle line:90%


00:13:48.990 --> 00:13:56.880 align:middle line:84%
But now you see if
you're looking at--

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:07.770 align:middle line:84%
if take-- if you now
look at little n that

00:14:07.770 --> 00:14:16.500 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than capital N, then
you have that 1 minus a n.

00:14:16.500 --> 00:14:19.320 align:middle line:84%
Well, 1 minus a n,
actually, for all n,

00:14:19.320 --> 00:14:29.940 align:middle line:84%
this here is less than 1/10
to the power n because if n is

00:14:29.940 --> 00:14:36.820 align:middle line:84%
equal to 1, this here,
this is within 1/10 of one.

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:40.940 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, this here is
in 1/100 of 1, et cetera.

00:14:40.940 --> 00:14:43.820 align:middle line:90%
So we have this inequality.

00:14:43.820 --> 00:14:46.010 align:middle line:84%
It's actually
equality in this case.

00:14:46.010 --> 00:14:50.260 align:middle line:90%
This here is an equality.

00:14:50.260 --> 00:14:54.170 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
this thing here,

00:14:54.170 --> 00:15:00.310 align:middle line:84%
this is obviously 1/10 to the
power n is less than or equal

00:15:00.310 --> 00:15:01.930 align:middle line:90%
to--

00:15:01.930 --> 00:15:06.160 align:middle line:90%
is less than 1 over n.

00:15:06.160 --> 00:15:09.790 align:middle line:84%
And so if little n is
bigger than capital N,

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:13.490 align:middle line:84%
this is therefore less
than 1 over capital N.

00:15:13.490 --> 00:15:15.940 align:middle line:90%
But this is less than epsilon.

00:15:15.940 --> 00:15:18.520 align:middle line:84%
And that's what
we need to prove.

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:19.660 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:15:19.660 --> 00:15:23.200 align:middle line:84%
So for the given, for
your given epsilon,

00:15:23.200 --> 00:15:27.160 align:middle line:84%
I specify a capital
N. And then we

00:15:27.160 --> 00:15:30.850 align:middle line:84%
need to prove that if little n
is bigger than our capital N,

00:15:30.850 --> 00:15:34.135 align:middle line:84%
then we come within
epsilon of the limit.

00:15:34.135 --> 00:15:34.635 align:middle line:90%
OK?

00:15:34.635 --> 00:15:41.550 align:middle line:90%


00:15:41.550 --> 00:15:45.390 align:middle line:84%
Now let me prove
a little theorem

00:15:45.390 --> 00:15:49.166 align:middle line:90%
about convergence sequences.

00:15:49.166 --> 00:15:56.340 align:middle line:90%


00:15:56.340 --> 00:16:01.110 align:middle line:84%
And this is like, if you
will, this little Lemma

00:16:01.110 --> 00:16:06.120 align:middle line:84%
is like the first test
for whether a sequence is

00:16:06.120 --> 00:16:07.560 align:middle line:90%
convergent.

00:16:07.560 --> 00:16:08.253 align:middle line:90%
So theorem.

00:16:08.253 --> 00:16:13.620 align:middle line:90%


00:16:13.620 --> 00:16:37.990 align:middle line:84%
If a n is a convergent
sequence, then a n is bounded.

00:16:37.990 --> 00:16:38.710 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:16:38.710 --> 00:16:40.370 align:middle line:84%
Let me explain what
I mean by that.

00:16:40.370 --> 00:16:46.700 align:middle line:84%
I mean that then the set of a
n-- so let me just explain that.

00:16:46.700 --> 00:17:00.970 align:middle line:84%
So then the set a1, a2, a3,
et cetera, this set here

00:17:00.970 --> 00:17:01.785 align:middle line:90%
is bounded.

00:17:01.785 --> 00:17:07.240 align:middle line:90%


00:17:07.240 --> 00:17:13.670 align:middle line:84%
It's not enough to be
bounded to be convergent

00:17:13.670 --> 00:17:16.060 align:middle line:90%
but it is a necessary criterion.

00:17:16.060 --> 00:17:21.280 align:middle line:90%


00:17:21.280 --> 00:17:23.980 align:middle line:84%
Let me, just as a
side remark, say

00:17:23.980 --> 00:17:27.970 align:middle line:84%
that if you're looking
at the sequence a n

00:17:27.970 --> 00:17:30.260 align:middle line:84%
that we looked at
just a minute ago,

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:34.770 align:middle line:84%
this here that is alternating
between minus 1 and 1,

00:17:34.770 --> 00:17:37.740 align:middle line:84%
this is a bounded sequence
because the value-- there's

00:17:37.740 --> 00:17:38.740 align:middle line:90%
only two values.

00:17:38.740 --> 00:17:42.250 align:middle line:84%
So it's obviously bounded
but it's not convergent.

00:17:42.250 --> 00:17:47.700 align:middle line:84%
But it is a necessary for a
sequence to be convergent.

00:17:47.700 --> 00:17:55.890 align:middle line:84%
It's necessary that the sequence
of numbers here is bounded.

00:17:55.890 --> 00:18:00.138 align:middle line:90%


00:18:00.138 --> 00:18:02.015 align:middle line:90%
So now let's try to prove that.

00:18:02.015 --> 00:18:06.870 align:middle line:90%


00:18:06.870 --> 00:18:17.730 align:middle line:84%
So we have-- so since
a n is convergent,

00:18:17.730 --> 00:18:23.730 align:middle line:84%
then there is some a so that
a n converges to this a.

00:18:23.730 --> 00:18:26.370 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:18:26.370 --> 00:18:31.950 align:middle line:84%
And so now I can just focus
on one single epsilon.

00:18:31.950 --> 00:18:53.780 align:middle line:84%
So in particular, if we choose
epsilon to be equal to 1,

00:18:53.780 --> 00:18:59.720 align:middle line:84%
then there exist capital N
so that if little n is bigger

00:18:59.720 --> 00:19:08.460 align:middle line:84%
than this capital N, then a
little n minus a is less than 1.

00:19:08.460 --> 00:19:12.200 align:middle line:84%
This is there is
convergence just applied

00:19:12.200 --> 00:19:14.070 align:middle line:90%
to this single epsilon.

00:19:14.070 --> 00:19:15.795 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:19:15.795 --> 00:19:16.295 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:19:16.295 --> 00:19:21.120 align:middle line:90%


00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:23.130 align:middle line:84%
So this is the
first observation.

00:19:23.130 --> 00:19:27.590 align:middle line:84%
The second observation is
that if we now look at all the

00:19:27.590 --> 00:19:31.060 align:middle line:84%
a n that are not
considered here--

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:38.010 align:middle line:84%
so if you're looking
at the set, this

00:19:38.010 --> 00:19:46.130 align:middle line:84%
is the first a
capital N minus 1 a n.

00:19:46.130 --> 00:19:46.630 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:19:46.630 --> 00:19:49.530 align:middle line:84%
Those are the ones that
doesn't fall in under,

00:19:49.530 --> 00:19:53.470 align:middle line:84%
that this little n is
bigger than the capital N.

00:19:53.470 --> 00:19:55.685 align:middle line:90%
So this set here is finite.

00:19:55.685 --> 00:19:58.920 align:middle line:90%


00:19:58.920 --> 00:20:02.640 align:middle line:84%
So obviously, so
for any finite set,

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:19.110 align:middle line:84%
you have that so they exist c,
a real number such that a n is

00:20:19.110 --> 00:20:23.020 align:middle line:84%
less than or equal to c
for any of these guys,

00:20:23.020 --> 00:20:33.100 align:middle line:84%
for any a in this, any
a n in this finite set.

00:20:33.100 --> 00:20:43.170 align:middle line:90%


00:20:43.170 --> 00:20:45.770 align:middle line:84%
In other words,
this means that a n

00:20:45.770 --> 00:20:53.485 align:middle line:84%
is less than or equal to c if n
here is between 1 and n minus 1.

00:20:53.485 --> 00:20:57.924 align:middle line:90%


00:20:57.924 --> 00:21:02.330 align:middle line:90%
So now I look at--

00:21:02.330 --> 00:21:05.240 align:middle line:90%
so now I look at--

00:21:05.240 --> 00:21:12.860 align:middle line:84%
now I want to look at the
numbers a n and this number

00:21:12.860 --> 00:21:14.690 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:21:14.690 --> 00:21:18.500 align:middle line:84%
And I want to look
at-- so I'm thinking

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:27.300 align:middle line:84%
about the set a n absolute
value and where in here

00:21:27.300 --> 00:21:33.990 align:middle line:90%
is one of two, 1, 2, cetera.

00:21:33.990 --> 00:21:37.650 align:middle line:84%
Well, I claim that
this thing here, I

00:21:37.650 --> 00:21:40.300 align:middle line:84%
can now prove that this
set here is bounded.

00:21:40.300 --> 00:21:46.230 align:middle line:84%
And this is just because that
the first n minus 1, those

00:21:46.230 --> 00:21:48.030 align:middle line:90%
are bounded by c.

00:21:48.030 --> 00:21:50.410 align:middle line:90%
So I claim that this set here--

00:21:50.410 --> 00:21:51.410 align:middle line:90%
so claim.

00:21:51.410 --> 00:21:54.750 align:middle line:90%


00:21:54.750 --> 00:22:11.490 align:middle line:84%
So that's the sup of this set
where n from 1 right over all

00:22:11.490 --> 00:22:13.080 align:middle line:90%
n's.

00:22:13.080 --> 00:22:22.980 align:middle line:84%
The sup of this set is less
than or equal to the max

00:22:22.980 --> 00:22:29.100 align:middle line:84%
of c and a plus normal,
absolute value of a plus 1.

00:22:29.100 --> 00:22:31.790 align:middle line:90%
So I claim that.

00:22:31.790 --> 00:22:37.580 align:middle line:84%
Now this is clearly, if you're
taking the first n minus 1,

00:22:37.580 --> 00:22:42.750 align:middle line:84%
then we already know that
they are bounded by c.

00:22:42.750 --> 00:22:45.410 align:middle line:84%
So you just need to
worry about the one

00:22:45.410 --> 00:22:48.380 align:middle line:90%
starting at capital N. Right?

00:22:48.380 --> 00:22:53.160 align:middle line:84%
So we only need to
worry about when.

00:22:53.160 --> 00:22:58.050 align:middle line:84%
So this is obviously the case
for the first capital N minus 1.

00:22:58.050 --> 00:23:00.620 align:middle line:90%
So we only need to worry about--

00:23:00.620 --> 00:23:15.170 align:middle line:84%
only need to show
this for little n

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:17.870 align:middle line:90%
larger than capital N. Larger.

00:23:17.870 --> 00:23:18.785 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:18.785 --> 00:23:20.870 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you explain
in the max over there

00:23:20.870 --> 00:23:23.665 align:middle line:84%
why there's the absolute value
of a plus-- like, the plus 1?

00:23:23.665 --> 00:23:24.540 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:23:24.540 --> 00:23:25.590 align:middle line:90%
I will explain this.

00:23:25.590 --> 00:23:27.450 align:middle line:90%
And I'll get to this.

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:28.690 align:middle line:90%
This is part of the proof.

00:23:28.690 --> 00:23:29.190 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:23:29.190 --> 00:23:31.900 align:middle line:84%
So it hopefully will
be clear in a minute.

00:23:31.900 --> 00:23:34.500 align:middle line:84%
If it's not, you
should complain.

00:23:34.500 --> 00:23:40.330 align:middle line:84%
So I only need to prove that
when I'm just looking at the set

00:23:40.330 --> 00:23:40.830 align:middle line:90%
here.

00:23:40.830 --> 00:23:43.800 align:middle line:84%
And I'm starting
at capital N, then

00:23:43.800 --> 00:23:47.460 align:middle line:90%
the sup is bounded like that.

00:23:47.460 --> 00:23:49.590 align:middle line:90%
And so then I--

00:23:49.590 --> 00:23:53.910 align:middle line:90%
so I'm looking at a n.

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:56.770 align:middle line:90%
But a n I can write as a n.

00:23:56.770 --> 00:24:00.120 align:middle line:84%
I can write in a
stupid way I can write

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:06.170 align:middle line:90%
a n as a n minus a plus a.

00:24:06.170 --> 00:24:06.670 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:24:06.670 --> 00:24:07.880 align:middle line:90%
So I can write it like that.

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:10.548 align:middle line:90%


00:24:10.548 --> 00:24:12.770 align:middle line:90%
And then I can just--

00:24:12.770 --> 00:24:13.270 align:middle line:90%
right.

00:24:13.270 --> 00:24:15.460 align:middle line:90%
So I have the sum of two things.

00:24:15.460 --> 00:24:20.630 align:middle line:84%
The absolute value is less
than the absolute value--

00:24:20.630 --> 00:24:23.990 align:middle line:90%
the sum of the absolute values.

00:24:23.990 --> 00:24:25.520 align:middle line:90%
So I have this.

00:24:25.520 --> 00:24:26.840 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:24:26.840 --> 00:24:30.500 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
since little n is bigger

00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:33.200 align:middle line:84%
than this capital
N, this capital N

00:24:33.200 --> 00:24:36.530 align:middle line:84%
was chosen so that this
here was bounded by 1.

00:24:36.530 --> 00:24:39.690 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
is less than 1.

00:24:39.690 --> 00:24:43.760 align:middle line:84%
And this here is less than
the absolute value of a.

00:24:43.760 --> 00:24:45.350 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:24:45.350 --> 00:24:50.190 align:middle line:84%
And so we have for the whole
tail starting at capital N,

00:24:50.190 --> 00:24:53.810 align:middle line:84%
we have that this thing
here is bounded by 1

00:24:53.810 --> 00:24:56.130 align:middle line:90%
plus the absolute value of a.

00:24:56.130 --> 00:25:03.240 align:middle line:84%
And for the remaining capital N
minus 1, those are bounded by C.

00:25:03.240 --> 00:25:09.110 align:middle line:84%
And so together, all of this
is bounded by the maximum

00:25:09.110 --> 00:25:12.170 align:middle line:90%
of these two things.

00:25:12.170 --> 00:25:14.040 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:25:14.040 --> 00:25:16.100 align:middle line:84%
Now the next thing
I want to talk about

00:25:16.100 --> 00:25:22.470 align:middle line:84%
is some sort of algebraic
property of limits

00:25:22.470 --> 00:25:24.140 align:middle line:90%
that is often very useful.

00:25:24.140 --> 00:25:26.940 align:middle line:90%


00:25:26.940 --> 00:25:29.555 align:middle line:84%
And I will prove--
there's four of these.

00:25:29.555 --> 00:25:32.070 align:middle line:90%


00:25:32.070 --> 00:25:34.810 align:middle line:90%
And I will prove two of them.

00:25:34.810 --> 00:25:41.165 align:middle line:84%
And the other one I will
outline the proof of.

00:25:41.165 --> 00:25:43.595 align:middle line:90%


00:25:43.595 --> 00:25:44.970 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE],
professor.

00:25:44.970 --> 00:25:45.803 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yep.

00:25:45.803 --> 00:25:50.580 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So in that the
claim was that the sup is--

00:25:50.580 --> 00:25:51.670 align:middle line:90%
the sup is less than.

00:25:51.670 --> 00:25:53.010 align:middle line:90%
So we don't need to--

00:25:53.010 --> 00:25:53.370 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah.

00:25:53.370 --> 00:25:53.580 align:middle line:90%
No.

00:25:53.580 --> 00:25:55.340 align:middle line:84%
You don't need to
actually find the sup.

00:25:55.340 --> 00:25:55.840 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:25:55.840 --> 00:25:56.950 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:25:56.950 --> 00:26:01.050 align:middle line:84%
And the reason I want to
write sup and not maximum

00:26:01.050 --> 00:26:04.080 align:middle line:84%
is that, of course, if
it's infinite numbers,

00:26:04.080 --> 00:26:06.850 align:middle line:84%
it's not clear
there is a maximum.

00:26:06.850 --> 00:26:11.340 align:middle line:84%
So we need to use
the terminology sup.

00:26:11.340 --> 00:26:15.780 align:middle line:84%
So that max of C and S
a plus 1 is not the sup.

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:17.320 align:middle line:90%
No no that's right.

00:26:17.320 --> 00:26:19.260 align:middle line:90%
It's a bound for the sup.

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:22.923 align:middle line:90%
But the sup presumably is less.

00:26:22.923 --> 00:26:24.840 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: And one that
really is just epsilon.

00:26:24.840 --> 00:26:27.390 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: And the
one really, to some extent,

00:26:27.390 --> 00:26:28.800 align:middle line:90%
could be almost anything.

00:26:28.800 --> 00:26:29.300 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:31.380 align:middle line:90%
It came from the epsilon.

00:26:31.380 --> 00:26:34.820 align:middle line:84%
But you see if you made
that epsilon smaller

00:26:34.820 --> 00:26:40.500 align:middle line:84%
then probably the c would jump
up because that is-- right.

00:26:40.500 --> 00:26:44.310 align:middle line:84%
Because the c was the maximum
of the first n minus 1.

00:26:44.310 --> 00:26:46.220 align:middle line:84%
So if you are further
out, then there

00:26:46.220 --> 00:26:49.340 align:middle line:84%
are more numbers that you're
taking the maximum over.

00:26:49.340 --> 00:26:50.630 align:middle line:90%
So anyway.

00:26:50.630 --> 00:26:53.150 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:26:53.150 --> 00:26:54.380 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:26:54.380 --> 00:26:58.106 align:middle line:84%
So we want to prove some
algebraic properties.

00:26:58.106 --> 00:27:08.390 align:middle line:90%


00:27:08.390 --> 00:27:09.115 align:middle line:90%
Of limits.

00:27:09.115 --> 00:27:14.430 align:middle line:90%


00:27:14.430 --> 00:27:17.440 align:middle line:90%
So the idea is that we take--

00:27:17.440 --> 00:27:20.470 align:middle line:90%
so we have four of these.

00:27:20.470 --> 00:27:24.260 align:middle line:84%
And the first one is
that you take a sequence.

00:27:24.260 --> 00:27:29.170 align:middle line:84%
So maybe I'll just say
throughout a n and bn

00:27:29.170 --> 00:27:30.306 align:middle line:90%
are sequences.

00:27:30.306 --> 00:27:35.230 align:middle line:90%


00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:45.012 align:middle line:84%
And a n is convergent to a
and bn is convergent to b.

00:27:45.012 --> 00:27:48.130 align:middle line:90%


00:27:48.130 --> 00:27:50.950 align:middle line:84%
The first one,
the first property

00:27:50.950 --> 00:27:53.330 align:middle line:84%
is that if you take a
real number-- sorry.

00:27:53.330 --> 00:27:57.430 align:middle line:84%
If you take a real number--
c here is a real number--

00:27:57.430 --> 00:28:00.760 align:middle line:84%
and you form a
new sequence where

00:28:00.760 --> 00:28:05.770 align:middle line:84%
CN is just this real
number times a n

00:28:05.770 --> 00:28:10.060 align:middle line:84%
so each cn is somehow
almost like a n except

00:28:10.060 --> 00:28:13.700 align:middle line:84%
that they're multiplied
by this fixed constant c.

00:28:13.700 --> 00:28:21.200 align:middle line:84%
So this here-- so the first one
is that cn is also convergent.

00:28:21.200 --> 00:28:26.360 align:middle line:90%
And the limit is just c times a.

00:28:26.360 --> 00:28:28.490 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:28.490 --> 00:28:35.210 align:middle line:84%
The second one is
that if you take--

00:28:35.210 --> 00:28:38.450 align:middle line:84%
if you define a
sequence-- so this

00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:40.470 align:middle line:84%
is a different
sequence than this one.

00:28:40.470 --> 00:28:46.670 align:middle line:84%
But if you define a sequence
cn by its a n, the n-th element

00:28:46.670 --> 00:28:51.050 align:middle line:84%
is a n plus bn,
then this sequence

00:28:51.050 --> 00:28:54.710 align:middle line:84%
is also convergent.
cn is convergent

00:28:54.710 --> 00:28:57.380 align:middle line:90%
and the limit is a plus b.

00:28:57.380 --> 00:28:58.960 align:middle line:90%
So that was the second property.

00:28:58.960 --> 00:29:12.320 align:middle line:90%


00:29:12.320 --> 00:29:14.041 align:middle line:90%
The third property is--

00:29:14.041 --> 00:29:19.790 align:middle line:90%


00:29:19.790 --> 00:29:22.220 align:middle line:84%
the third property is that
if you take a product.

00:29:22.220 --> 00:29:22.840 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:29:22.840 --> 00:29:25.030 align:middle line:90%
So if you take a n--

00:29:25.030 --> 00:29:31.100 align:middle line:84%
if you define cn
as a n times bn--

00:29:31.100 --> 00:29:33.100 align:middle line:90%
so this is a new sequence.

00:29:33.100 --> 00:29:40.870 align:middle line:84%
Then cn is convergent and
the limit is a times b.

00:29:40.870 --> 00:29:53.290 align:middle line:84%
And the last property
is that if the a n are--

00:29:53.290 --> 00:29:56.980 align:middle line:84%
all of these are
different from 0.

00:29:56.980 --> 00:29:59.205 align:middle line:90%
So this here is for all n.

00:29:59.205 --> 00:30:02.500 align:middle line:90%


00:30:02.500 --> 00:30:09.460 align:middle line:84%
And also you have that the
limit here is not equal to 0.

00:30:09.460 --> 00:30:17.300 align:middle line:84%
Then if you define a
sequence to be 1 over a n,

00:30:17.300 --> 00:30:22.310 align:middle line:84%
then cn here converge and
the limit is 1 over n.

00:30:22.310 --> 00:30:25.520 align:middle line:90%


00:30:25.520 --> 00:30:29.820 align:middle line:84%
And so I will prove
rigorously the first two.

00:30:29.820 --> 00:30:33.300 align:middle line:84%
And I will basically tell you
how to prove the other two.

00:30:33.300 --> 00:30:38.510 align:middle line:84%
But the first two
I will write out

00:30:38.510 --> 00:30:43.070 align:middle line:84%
formally, as we talked about
last time, how you write

00:30:43.070 --> 00:30:49.070 align:middle line:84%
a formal proof, whereas what
I'm going to discuss for three

00:30:49.070 --> 00:30:52.410 align:middle line:84%
and four is very, very
close to a formal proof

00:30:52.410 --> 00:30:53.870 align:middle line:84%
but it's more like
what you would

00:30:53.870 --> 00:30:55.525 align:middle line:90%
have on a piece of scrap paper.

00:30:55.525 --> 00:31:10.660 align:middle line:90%


00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:12.480 align:middle line:84%
So now let's prove
the first one.

00:31:12.480 --> 00:31:15.130 align:middle line:90%


00:31:15.130 --> 00:31:16.620 align:middle line:90%
So proof of one.

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:30.940 align:middle line:90%


00:31:30.940 --> 00:31:35.145 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon
greater than 0--

00:31:35.145 --> 00:31:39.800 align:middle line:90%


00:31:39.800 --> 00:31:41.330 align:middle line:90%
so yeah.

00:31:41.330 --> 00:31:45.850 align:middle line:84%
So first of all, of
course, if this capital C--

00:31:45.850 --> 00:31:50.600 align:middle line:84%
if this capital C is 0,
then everything is 0.

00:31:50.600 --> 00:31:53.300 align:middle line:90%
So it's trivially the case.

00:31:53.300 --> 00:31:55.570 align:middle line:90%
So we may as well assume.

00:31:55.570 --> 00:31:58.790 align:middle line:84%
So may as well assume
that capital C--

00:31:58.790 --> 00:32:03.700 align:middle line:90%


00:32:03.700 --> 00:32:05.265 align:middle line:90%
that capital C is not 0.

00:32:05.265 --> 00:32:09.170 align:middle line:90%


00:32:09.170 --> 00:32:12.390 align:middle line:84%
So now, given epsilon
greater than 0,

00:32:12.390 --> 00:32:16.680 align:middle line:84%
since this sequence a
n is converging to a,

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:26.790 align:middle line:84%
this means that there
exists n such that--

00:32:26.790 --> 00:32:29.430 align:middle line:84%
and now I'm not going
to use that epsilon.

00:32:29.430 --> 00:32:31.640 align:middle line:90%
You gave me that epsilon.

00:32:31.640 --> 00:32:35.600 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to use that
epsilon in the definition

00:32:35.600 --> 00:32:38.190 align:middle line:90%
that a n is converging to a.

00:32:38.190 --> 00:32:40.310 align:middle line:84%
I'm not going to use
that one, but I'm

00:32:40.310 --> 00:32:42.840 align:middle line:84%
going to use one that
is closely related.

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:47.120 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to use epsilon
divided by the norm of z

00:32:47.120 --> 00:32:50.000 align:middle line:90%
because that's another positive.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:53.250 align:middle line:90%
So you gave me an epsilon.

00:32:53.250 --> 00:32:56.990 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to look
at this number here.

00:32:56.990 --> 00:32:59.630 align:middle line:90%
That's a positive number.

00:32:59.630 --> 00:33:03.230 align:middle line:84%
And I can use that
in the definition

00:33:03.230 --> 00:33:05.610 align:middle line:90%
that a n converges to a.

00:33:05.610 --> 00:33:09.680 align:middle line:84%
So I'm going to say that
because an converts to a,

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:13.720 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital N such
that if little n is bigger

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:23.470 align:middle line:84%
than this capital N, then a n
minus a is less than epsilon

00:33:23.470 --> 00:33:26.950 align:middle line:90%
over capital S--

00:33:26.950 --> 00:33:31.940 align:middle line:84%
or C, sorry, capital
C, a normal capital C.

00:33:31.940 --> 00:33:35.540 align:middle line:84%
But now I just
multiply on both sides.

00:33:35.540 --> 00:33:46.540 align:middle line:84%
So multiply by the
absolute value of capital C

00:33:46.540 --> 00:33:47.610 align:middle line:90%
on both sides.

00:33:47.610 --> 00:33:52.240 align:middle line:90%


00:33:52.240 --> 00:33:58.050 align:middle line:84%
And so if we do that,
then this here pops in.

00:33:58.050 --> 00:33:58.550 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:33:58.550 --> 00:34:04.880 align:middle line:84%
It actually goes in as c
times a n minus c times a

00:34:04.880 --> 00:34:07.880 align:middle line:90%
is less than epsilon.

00:34:07.880 --> 00:34:11.090 align:middle line:84%
And this is as
long as this n is--

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:13.070 align:middle line:84%
little n is bigger
than that capital

00:34:13.070 --> 00:34:15.770 align:middle line:84%
N. This is exactly what
we wanted to prove.

00:34:15.770 --> 00:34:18.350 align:middle line:90%


00:34:18.350 --> 00:34:19.940 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:34:19.940 --> 00:34:23.253 align:middle line:90%
Now the second one is--

00:34:23.253 --> 00:34:33.080 align:middle line:90%


00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:39.050 align:middle line:84%
so the reason why I'm
doing the first two--

00:34:39.050 --> 00:34:42.030 align:middle line:84%
you see that those are
pretty straightforward.

00:34:42.030 --> 00:34:47.929 align:middle line:84%
I mean, it's not like any of
these is complicated to prove.

00:34:47.929 --> 00:34:52.074 align:middle line:84%
The next two is a
little bit more--

00:34:52.074 --> 00:34:54.199 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I wouldn't say
complicated but a little bit

00:34:54.199 --> 00:34:55.860 align:middle line:90%
more involved, these two.

00:34:55.860 --> 00:34:58.490 align:middle line:84%
But I want to give you
the idea because it's

00:34:58.490 --> 00:35:04.390 align:middle line:84%
kind of a very simple but
useful idea in these two.

00:35:04.390 --> 00:35:06.920 align:middle line:84%
So I don't want
to skip the proof.

00:35:06.920 --> 00:35:11.050 align:middle line:90%


00:35:11.050 --> 00:35:17.040 align:middle line:84%
So we want to approve
of the second property.

00:35:17.040 --> 00:35:27.920 align:middle line:90%


00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:30.760 align:middle line:84%
So we have that
a n is converging

00:35:30.760 --> 00:35:34.660 align:middle line:90%
to a and bn is converging to b.

00:35:34.660 --> 00:35:37.240 align:middle line:84%
And so again, you
give me an epsilon

00:35:37.240 --> 00:35:39.040 align:middle line:90%
that I have to work with.

00:35:39.040 --> 00:35:46.840 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon-- given
epsilon greater than zero,

00:35:46.840 --> 00:35:52.060 align:middle line:84%
then I'm going to not again use
this epsilon in the definition

00:35:52.060 --> 00:35:53.960 align:middle line:90%
that a n converge to a.

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:56.470 align:middle line:84%
And I'm not going to
use it in the definition

00:35:56.470 --> 00:36:01.920 align:middle line:84%
that bn is converging to b, but
I'm going to use epsilon over 2

00:36:01.920 --> 00:36:03.400 align:middle line:90%
in each of them.

00:36:03.400 --> 00:36:17.310 align:middle line:84%
So since a n converts to a,
there exists a capital N--

00:36:17.310 --> 00:36:21.560 align:middle line:84%
and let me call it
capital N subscript a--

00:36:21.560 --> 00:36:29.310 align:middle line:84%
such that if little n is
bigger than this capital N

00:36:29.310 --> 00:36:38.835 align:middle line:84%
subscript a, then a n minus a
is less than epsilon over 2.

00:36:38.835 --> 00:36:39.335 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:36:39.335 --> 00:37:00.340 align:middle line:90%


00:37:00.340 --> 00:37:16.000 align:middle line:84%
Likewise, since being
converted to b, then

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:21.170 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital
N, but denoted by this,

00:37:21.170 --> 00:37:24.370 align:middle line:84%
it may be different than the
one coming from the sequence

00:37:24.370 --> 00:37:35.140 align:middle line:84%
a n such that if little n is
bigger than this capital N

00:37:35.140 --> 00:37:45.280 align:middle line:84%
subscript b, then bn minus b
is smaller than epsilon over 2.

00:37:45.280 --> 00:37:50.600 align:middle line:90%
And so now I have to choose.

00:37:50.600 --> 00:37:52.060 align:middle line:90%
So you gave me the epsilon.

00:37:52.060 --> 00:37:55.630 align:middle line:84%
And I have to choose a capital
N. I haven't chosen that yet

00:37:55.630 --> 00:37:58.750 align:middle line:90%
but I will do that now.

00:37:58.750 --> 00:38:08.670 align:middle line:84%
So set capital N equal to
the maximum of these two N's.

00:38:08.670 --> 00:38:12.510 align:middle line:84%
So you're setting it equal
to the maximum of these two.

00:38:12.510 --> 00:38:15.000 align:middle line:90%
Now if little n--

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:21.210 align:middle line:84%
so then for little n
bigger than this capital N,

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:25.360 align:middle line:84%
if you're looking at a--
so now we want to look at--

00:38:25.360 --> 00:38:30.880 align:middle line:84%
so our sequence cn was
the sum of these two.

00:38:30.880 --> 00:38:33.160 align:middle line:90%
so this here was cn.

00:38:33.160 --> 00:38:36.310 align:middle line:90%
So we want to prove that--

00:38:36.310 --> 00:38:40.150 align:middle line:84%
so we want to look at
cn minus a times b.

00:38:40.150 --> 00:38:43.890 align:middle line:84%
And we want to prove that if
little n is bigger than this,

00:38:43.890 --> 00:38:47.470 align:middle line:84%
then this here is strictly
less than epsilon.

00:38:47.470 --> 00:38:54.510 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here is cn was,
by definition, a n plus bn.

00:38:54.510 --> 00:38:55.110 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:38:55.110 --> 00:38:56.470 align:middle line:90%
And this was not the product.

00:38:56.470 --> 00:38:57.115 align:middle line:90%
It was the sum.

00:38:57.115 --> 00:39:00.613 align:middle line:90%


00:39:00.613 --> 00:39:05.740 align:middle line:90%
Minus a plus b.

00:39:05.740 --> 00:39:09.190 align:middle line:84%
But this thing
here you can write

00:39:09.190 --> 00:39:16.620 align:middle line:90%
as a n minus a plus bn minus b.

00:39:16.620 --> 00:39:19.540 align:middle line:90%


00:39:19.540 --> 00:39:22.465 align:middle line:84%
And now you can just take
the absolute value of this.

00:39:22.465 --> 00:39:24.465 align:middle line:84%
It's bounded by the
absolute value of the first.

00:39:24.465 --> 00:39:37.420 align:middle line:90%


00:39:37.420 --> 00:39:40.280 align:middle line:84%
So plus the absolute
value of this thing.

00:39:40.280 --> 00:39:45.400 align:middle line:90%


00:39:45.400 --> 00:39:54.310 align:middle line:84%
And now you see
that if little a--

00:39:54.310 --> 00:39:59.150 align:middle line:90%
let me keep-- so if little a--

00:39:59.150 --> 00:39:59.650 align:middle line:90%
sorry.

00:39:59.650 --> 00:40:05.070 align:middle line:84%
If little n-- since little n
is bigger than capital N, which

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:09.310 align:middle line:84%
is bigger than capital
N of a, in particular,

00:40:09.310 --> 00:40:13.690 align:middle line:84%
then this thing here is
less than epsilon over 2.

00:40:13.690 --> 00:40:23.940 align:middle line:84%
So you have that cn minus a
plus b is less than epsilon

00:40:23.940 --> 00:40:26.280 align:middle line:90%
over 2 that comes from this.

00:40:26.280 --> 00:40:34.440 align:middle line:84%
But you also have that capital
N is bigger or equal to n sub b.

00:40:34.440 --> 00:40:37.590 align:middle line:84%
So you also have that this
thing here is less than epsilon

00:40:37.590 --> 00:40:38.430 align:middle line:90%
over 2.

00:40:38.430 --> 00:40:40.710 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:40:40.710 --> 00:40:44.550 align:middle line:84%
So you have that this
thing here with little a

00:40:44.550 --> 00:40:48.550 align:middle line:84%
is big N-- is bigger than this
capital N. This thing here,

00:40:48.550 --> 00:40:51.580 align:middle line:84%
this difference is
strictly less than epsilon.

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:53.740 align:middle line:84%
That's what we needed
to prove in order

00:40:53.740 --> 00:40:56.380 align:middle line:84%
to prove that the sequence
that was the sum of the two

00:40:56.380 --> 00:40:59.660 align:middle line:84%
sequences converging to
the sum of the limits.

00:40:59.660 --> 00:41:00.580 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:41:00.580 --> 00:41:05.050 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: We initially defined
the n minus [? e ?] or n minus a

00:41:05.050 --> 00:41:06.880 align:middle line:90%
be less than epsilon over 2.

00:41:06.880 --> 00:41:08.800 align:middle line:84%
What was the
justification for why

00:41:08.800 --> 00:41:13.510 align:middle line:84%
we would say if we know that
the n converge to be within?

00:41:13.510 --> 00:41:14.530 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

00:41:14.530 --> 00:41:15.170 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:41:15.170 --> 00:41:21.230 align:middle line:84%
So because a n or bn,
because they converge.

00:41:21.230 --> 00:41:25.090 align:middle line:90%
So let's say a n converges to a.

00:41:25.090 --> 00:41:25.820 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:41:25.820 --> 00:41:29.360 align:middle line:84%
Then for all epsilon,
you gave me the epsilon.

00:41:29.360 --> 00:41:31.960 align:middle line:84%
And I'm using that
it's converging

00:41:31.960 --> 00:41:35.420 align:middle line:84%
not just for that
choice of epsilon

00:41:35.420 --> 00:41:38.030 align:middle line:84%
but also even for
epsilon over 2.

00:41:38.030 --> 00:41:41.980 align:middle line:84%
That epsilon, you
gave me the epsilon.

00:41:41.980 --> 00:41:44.090 align:middle line:84%
Then I'm using that
it's converging.

00:41:44.090 --> 00:41:46.210 align:middle line:84%
So I will have to
choose probably

00:41:46.210 --> 00:41:49.780 align:middle line:84%
an n that is much larger
if I'm using epsilon over 2

00:41:49.780 --> 00:41:52.400 align:middle line:84%
than if I use
directly the epsilon.

00:41:52.400 --> 00:41:54.120 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: So I'd assume
that it increases

00:41:54.120 --> 00:41:56.460 align:middle line:90%
like epsilon gets smaller.

00:41:56.460 --> 00:41:58.450 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: As
epsilon gets smaller,

00:41:58.450 --> 00:42:02.078 align:middle line:84%
presumably you need to
choose capital N larger.

00:42:02.078 --> 00:42:02.620 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:42:02.620 --> 00:42:04.470 align:middle line:84%
So you couldn't run
into a case where

00:42:04.470 --> 00:42:08.220 align:middle line:84%
we're assuming a convergence
is like smooth as opposed

00:42:08.220 --> 00:42:10.273 align:middle line:90%
to oscillating about a point?

00:42:10.273 --> 00:42:11.190 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Right.

00:42:11.190 --> 00:42:11.732 align:middle line:90%
That's right.

00:42:11.732 --> 00:42:19.170 align:middle line:84%
I mean, so-- but
I'm using that for--

00:42:19.170 --> 00:42:21.510 align:middle line:84%
I'm basically using
that for all epsilon,

00:42:21.510 --> 00:42:24.010 align:middle line:84%
that it wasn't just
for a fixed epsilon.

00:42:24.010 --> 00:42:28.170 align:middle line:84%
And so that's why, when you
came to this epsilon, then

00:42:28.170 --> 00:42:30.850 align:middle line:84%
I'm actually using it
for epsilon over 2.

00:42:30.850 --> 00:42:31.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:42:31.350 --> 00:42:33.900 align:middle line:90%


00:42:33.900 --> 00:42:34.570 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:42:34.570 --> 00:42:37.740 align:middle line:84%
So that was the
first two properties.

00:42:37.740 --> 00:42:42.060 align:middle line:84%
It's not like the other
one is super difficult.

00:42:42.060 --> 00:42:44.590 align:middle line:84%
But those two are the
most straightforward.

00:42:44.590 --> 00:42:47.430 align:middle line:90%
Let's look at the other two.

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:52.730 align:middle line:84%
And so in particular, because
it's like, for the next one,

00:42:52.730 --> 00:42:56.620 align:middle line:84%
there's a little
trick that is useful

00:42:56.620 --> 00:42:59.113 align:middle line:90%
in various different settings.

00:42:59.113 --> 00:43:04.270 align:middle line:90%


00:43:04.270 --> 00:43:11.110 align:middle line:84%
And so prove-- but the next
two I will just outline.

00:43:11.110 --> 00:43:13.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:43:13.690 --> 00:43:21.060 align:middle line:90%
So proof of 3 so outline.

00:43:21.060 --> 00:43:26.170 align:middle line:90%


00:43:26.170 --> 00:43:31.450 align:middle line:84%
So we need to look
at a n times bn.

00:43:31.450 --> 00:43:32.050 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:43:32.050 --> 00:43:35.030 align:middle line:90%
So cn is a n times bn.

00:43:35.030 --> 00:43:40.870 align:middle line:84%
And we want to compare
cn with a times b.

00:43:40.870 --> 00:43:44.620 align:middle line:84%
We want to show that this
thing here, if little n is

00:43:44.620 --> 00:43:45.740 align:middle line:90%
sufficiently large--

00:43:45.740 --> 00:43:49.870 align:middle line:84%
so given an epsilon, if little
n is sufficiently large,

00:43:49.870 --> 00:43:54.000 align:middle line:84%
then this difference
is bounded by epsilon.

00:43:54.000 --> 00:44:01.650 align:middle line:84%
But this thing here
is anbn minus a b.

00:44:01.650 --> 00:44:03.690 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:44:03.690 --> 00:44:07.530 align:middle line:84%
And so the little trick is
now that, in itself, it's

00:44:07.530 --> 00:44:11.440 align:middle line:84%
kind of difficult to
compare these two things.

00:44:11.440 --> 00:44:17.040 align:middle line:84%
But the little trick is that
if you're looking at anbn,

00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:20.280 align:middle line:90%
if you're sort of--

00:44:20.280 --> 00:44:22.450 align:middle line:84%
instead of comparing
them directly,

00:44:22.450 --> 00:44:25.260 align:middle line:84%
then comparing this
with something that

00:44:25.260 --> 00:44:30.270 align:middle line:84%
is halfway between this and
that, then it gets a lot easier.

00:44:30.270 --> 00:44:34.470 align:middle line:84%
So what you do is
you're looking at anbn,

00:44:34.470 --> 00:44:39.930 align:middle line:84%
and you subtract
a and b, and then

00:44:39.930 --> 00:44:41.450 align:middle line:90%
you add it immediately again.

00:44:41.450 --> 00:44:45.000 align:middle line:90%


00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:47.900 align:middle line:90%
So this is certainly the same.

00:44:47.900 --> 00:44:53.840 align:middle line:84%
And now I can write
this thing here as a n.

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:57.030 align:middle line:84%
I can just concentrate
on these two first.

00:44:57.030 --> 00:44:59.900 align:middle line:90%
And then I can factor out a n.

00:44:59.900 --> 00:45:01.630 align:middle line:90%
So I can write that as this.

00:45:01.630 --> 00:45:04.940 align:middle line:90%


00:45:04.940 --> 00:45:08.460 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here
I can factor out a b.

00:45:08.460 --> 00:45:12.410 align:middle line:90%


00:45:12.410 --> 00:45:16.340 align:middle line:90%
So I can write it like that.

00:45:16.340 --> 00:45:19.340 align:middle line:90%
And now you see this.

00:45:19.340 --> 00:45:21.030 align:middle line:90%
It looks much more promising.

00:45:21.030 --> 00:45:23.250 align:middle line:84%
This one looks like
the problematic one.

00:45:23.250 --> 00:45:25.790 align:middle line:84%
This one looks like
no problem at all

00:45:25.790 --> 00:45:29.310 align:middle line:84%
because this is just
some fixed constant times

00:45:29.310 --> 00:45:30.800 align:middle line:90%
this difference here.

00:45:30.800 --> 00:45:32.900 align:middle line:84%
This one looks a little
bit more problematic

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:34.320 align:middle line:84%
because it's not
a fixed constant.

00:45:34.320 --> 00:45:36.780 align:middle line:84%
But we can deal with
this in just a second.

00:45:36.780 --> 00:45:39.230 align:middle line:84%
But the first thing I
can do is I just take

00:45:39.230 --> 00:45:48.590 align:middle line:84%
the absolute value of this plus
the absolute value of that.

00:45:48.590 --> 00:45:52.830 align:middle line:90%


00:45:52.830 --> 00:45:55.000 align:middle line:90%
And now I just take--

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:00.190 align:middle line:84%
so then this here is actually
the same for a product.

00:46:00.190 --> 00:46:04.717 align:middle line:84%
You can just take the product
of the absolute value.

00:46:04.717 --> 00:46:05.300 align:middle line:90%
It's the same.

00:46:05.300 --> 00:46:17.540 align:middle line:90%


00:46:17.540 --> 00:46:24.060 align:middle line:84%
Now the next thing
is that we're going

00:46:24.060 --> 00:46:32.730 align:middle line:84%
to use the theorem
that we proved earlier

00:46:32.730 --> 00:46:41.850 align:middle line:90%
that since this sequence here--

00:46:41.850 --> 00:46:47.090 align:middle line:84%
since these numbers here,
all of these numbers for all,

00:46:47.090 --> 00:46:48.310 align:middle line:90%
when you take the set--

00:46:48.310 --> 00:46:51.830 align:middle line:90%


00:46:51.830 --> 00:46:58.233 align:middle line:84%
when you're looking at this set,
since this set here is bounded--

00:46:58.233 --> 00:47:01.190 align:middle line:90%


00:47:01.190 --> 00:47:04.890 align:middle line:84%
and it's bounded because
the sequence was convergent.

00:47:04.890 --> 00:47:09.350 align:middle line:84%
And so we already proved
that then the values, the set

00:47:09.350 --> 00:47:11.590 align:middle line:90%
of values is a bounded set.

00:47:11.590 --> 00:47:12.090 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:47:12.090 --> 00:47:13.620 align:middle line:90%
So it's bounded.

00:47:13.620 --> 00:47:15.500 align:middle line:90%
And so we can assume--

00:47:15.500 --> 00:47:33.080 align:middle line:84%
so that exists C. So that's a n
is the absolute value is bounded

00:47:33.080 --> 00:47:34.095 align:middle line:90%
by the c.

00:47:34.095 --> 00:47:38.870 align:middle line:90%


00:47:38.870 --> 00:47:40.025 align:middle line:90%
So now I have--

00:47:40.025 --> 00:47:42.790 align:middle line:90%


00:47:42.790 --> 00:47:51.120 align:middle line:84%
and so now I have that
cn minus a times b.

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:53.670 align:middle line:90%
This is what I had up there.

00:47:53.670 --> 00:47:55.300 align:middle line:90%
And I'm just using that.

00:47:55.300 --> 00:47:58.110 align:middle line:84%
This is now bounded by just
because these things here

00:47:58.110 --> 00:48:10.650 align:middle line:84%
are bounded by c, I get cbn
minus b plus b over a n minus a.

00:48:10.650 --> 00:48:12.750 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:48:12.750 --> 00:48:15.910 align:middle line:84%
And now you see now it's
going to follow like--

00:48:15.910 --> 00:48:18.660 align:middle line:84%
so this here was just
some observations.

00:48:18.660 --> 00:48:19.210 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:21.280 align:middle line:84%
And now when you
come to the proof,

00:48:21.280 --> 00:48:34.980 align:middle line:84%
so to prove three, then
given epsilon greater than 0,

00:48:34.980 --> 00:48:38.130 align:middle line:84%
now we want to make sure
that this thing here

00:48:38.130 --> 00:48:41.960 align:middle line:84%
is less than epsilon over
2 and that this thing here

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:44.090 align:middle line:90%
is less than epsilon over 2.

00:48:44.090 --> 00:48:49.790 align:middle line:84%
And so I don't want to get
in trouble if this set was 0

00:48:49.790 --> 00:48:51.510 align:middle line:90%
or if this set was 0.

00:48:51.510 --> 00:49:00.590 align:middle line:84%
So I'm just-- so given epsilon
since a n converges to a, then I

00:49:00.590 --> 00:49:04.820 align:middle line:90%
can find--

00:49:04.820 --> 00:49:06.840 align:middle line:84%
now I'm basically writing
out the whole proof,

00:49:06.840 --> 00:49:10.610 align:middle line:90%
but I can find capital An--

00:49:10.610 --> 00:49:15.290 align:middle line:84%
sorry-- capital Na so that if
little n is bigger than capital

00:49:15.290 --> 00:49:24.270 align:middle line:84%
Na, then you have that a
n minus a is less than--

00:49:24.270 --> 00:49:26.520 align:middle line:90%
I don't quite use that epsilon.

00:49:26.520 --> 00:49:29.160 align:middle line:84%
And I don't quite
use epsilon over 2,

00:49:29.160 --> 00:49:32.460 align:middle line:90%
but I take absolute value.

00:49:32.460 --> 00:49:37.820 align:middle line:84%
I multiply it like this because
I don't want to have something

00:49:37.820 --> 00:49:40.770 align:middle line:84%
where if b was was
zero, then it really

00:49:40.770 --> 00:49:42.490 align:middle line:84%
didn't make any
sense what I wrote.

00:49:42.490 --> 00:49:44.050 align:middle line:90%
So now there's no problem.

00:49:44.050 --> 00:49:46.200 align:middle line:84%
It definitely makes
sense even if b is 0.

00:49:46.200 --> 00:50:06.450 align:middle line:90%


00:50:06.450 --> 00:50:14.525 align:middle line:84%
Likewise since bn converges
to b, then there exists--

00:50:14.525 --> 00:50:17.460 align:middle line:90%


00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:20.560 align:middle line:84%
so again, you gave
me an epsilon.

00:50:20.560 --> 00:50:31.080 align:middle line:84%
So there exists an nb such that
if little n is bigger than nb,

00:50:31.080 --> 00:50:35.730 align:middle line:84%
then actually you
have that bn minus

00:50:35.730 --> 00:50:40.260 align:middle line:84%
b is less than
epsilon again over 2.

00:50:40.260 --> 00:50:42.380 align:middle line:84%
And this is not quite
what I use because I

00:50:42.380 --> 00:50:44.450 align:middle line:84%
don't want to be
in trouble that c--

00:50:44.450 --> 00:50:47.240 align:middle line:84%
c is already non-negative
because it's bigger

00:50:47.240 --> 00:50:48.600 align:middle line:90%
than this absolute value.

00:50:48.600 --> 00:50:52.370 align:middle line:84%
But I'm just adding one
for the same reason.

00:50:52.370 --> 00:50:59.930 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see that if
little n-- so therefore,

00:50:59.930 --> 00:51:04.130 align:middle line:84%
if little n is bigger than
the maximum of these two,

00:51:04.130 --> 00:51:08.150 align:middle line:84%
then both of these
inequalities hold.

00:51:08.150 --> 00:51:09.030 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:51:09.030 --> 00:51:10.500 align:middle line:90%
Both of them hold.

00:51:10.500 --> 00:51:16.370 align:middle line:84%
And so this means that you
now have that cn minus a times

00:51:16.370 --> 00:51:19.400 align:middle line:90%
b, this thing here.

00:51:19.400 --> 00:51:20.880 align:middle line:90%
So we had it here.

00:51:20.880 --> 00:51:24.380 align:middle line:90%
This is less than c.

00:51:24.380 --> 00:51:28.160 align:middle line:84%
And then this
difference here was now

00:51:28.160 --> 00:51:35.460 align:middle line:84%
assumed to be epsilon
over 2, 1 plus c.

00:51:35.460 --> 00:51:40.980 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, this
thing here is bounded

00:51:40.980 --> 00:51:46.290 align:middle line:90%
by this number here times--

00:51:46.290 --> 00:51:53.190 align:middle line:84%
and then this thing
here, so epsilon

00:51:53.190 --> 00:51:58.680 align:middle line:84%
over 2 absolute
value of b plus 1.

00:51:58.680 --> 00:52:00.905 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:00.905 --> 00:52:03.180 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that
this thing here,

00:52:03.180 --> 00:52:08.250 align:middle line:84%
that c divided by 1 plus
c, that's bounded by 1.

00:52:08.250 --> 00:52:08.920 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:12.635 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is
bounded by epsilon over 2.

00:52:12.635 --> 00:52:15.180 align:middle line:90%


00:52:15.180 --> 00:52:18.360 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here, same
reason is that this thing here

00:52:18.360 --> 00:52:21.570 align:middle line:90%
is bounded by epsilon over 2.

00:52:21.570 --> 00:52:25.650 align:middle line:84%
And so the whole thing
was bounded by epsilon

00:52:25.650 --> 00:52:31.300 align:middle line:84%
when little n was bigger than
the maximum of these two.

00:52:31.300 --> 00:52:36.360 align:middle line:84%
So in the end, I wrote
out the whole proof.

00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:38.420 align:middle line:84%
I already posted
the lecture notes.

00:52:38.420 --> 00:52:41.040 align:middle line:84%
In the lecture notes, I didn't
write out the whole proof

00:52:41.040 --> 00:52:42.240 align:middle line:90%
but I gave the idea.

00:52:42.240 --> 00:52:46.100 align:middle line:84%
So I stopped once we
were here and somewhere

00:52:46.100 --> 00:52:49.080 align:middle line:84%
here after this one
somewhere anyway.

00:52:49.080 --> 00:52:49.795 align:middle line:90%
But you see.

00:52:49.795 --> 00:52:54.530 align:middle line:90%


00:52:54.530 --> 00:52:57.080 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:52:57.080 --> 00:52:57.690 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:52:57.690 --> 00:53:02.630 align:middle line:84%
So the next thing I want to
talk about is that if you--

00:53:02.630 --> 00:53:05.100 align:middle line:84%
No, no, I still
need property four.

00:53:05.100 --> 00:53:06.120 align:middle line:90%
And that's also useful.

00:53:06.120 --> 00:53:06.620 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

00:53:06.620 --> 00:53:11.045 align:middle line:84%
So let's go through that and
then we'll come to subsequences.

00:53:11.045 --> 00:53:24.710 align:middle line:90%


00:53:24.710 --> 00:53:30.050 align:middle line:84%
So I want to prove that if you
take a sequence of real numbers

00:53:30.050 --> 00:53:31.740 align:middle line:90%
none of them is zero.

00:53:31.740 --> 00:53:37.090 align:middle line:84%
They converge and the limit is
not 0, then 1 over the sequence

00:53:37.090 --> 00:53:38.973 align:middle line:90%
is another convergence sequence.

00:53:38.973 --> 00:53:54.850 align:middle line:90%


00:53:54.850 --> 00:53:58.130 align:middle line:84%
But again, just
the main takeaway.

00:53:58.130 --> 00:54:01.040 align:middle line:84%
The main takeaway, I
think, from property,

00:54:01.040 --> 00:54:06.310 align:middle line:84%
this third property was that
this little idea about inserting

00:54:06.310 --> 00:54:08.950 align:middle line:84%
something that was halfway
between the two things you

00:54:08.950 --> 00:54:10.450 align:middle line:84%
were comparing
because they weren't

00:54:10.450 --> 00:54:12.440 align:middle line:90%
very easy to compare directly.

00:54:12.440 --> 00:54:14.200 align:middle line:84%
And that's like a
little trick that

00:54:14.200 --> 00:54:15.980 align:middle line:90%
is useful in various places.

00:54:15.980 --> 00:54:18.410 align:middle line:84%
It comes up almost
the same thing.

00:54:18.410 --> 00:54:21.430 align:middle line:84%
One place it comes up
is what's called Leibniz

00:54:21.430 --> 00:54:23.590 align:middle line:84%
rule that if you
take two functions,

00:54:23.590 --> 00:54:26.510 align:middle line:84%
and you take the product
of these two functions,

00:54:26.510 --> 00:54:31.040 align:middle line:84%
and you try to prove that one is
the derivative of the product,

00:54:31.040 --> 00:54:32.850 align:middle line:90%
it's exactly the same trick.

00:54:32.850 --> 00:54:38.420 align:middle line:84%
And it comes up various
other-- more fancy ways.

00:54:38.420 --> 00:54:44.990 align:middle line:84%
So now let's look at--
let's prove property four.

00:54:44.990 --> 00:54:47.270 align:middle line:90%
So property four.

00:54:47.270 --> 00:54:49.975 align:middle line:90%
Proof of property four.

00:54:49.975 --> 00:54:56.900 align:middle line:90%


00:54:56.900 --> 00:54:59.000 align:middle line:90%
So we have this.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:01.610 align:middle line:90%
So cn is 1 over n.

00:55:01.610 --> 00:55:05.250 align:middle line:84%
And we know that a n
are not equal to 0.

00:55:05.250 --> 00:55:07.140 align:middle line:84%
And we know that a
is not equal to 0.

00:55:07.140 --> 00:55:08.400 align:middle line:90%
This here makes sense.

00:55:08.400 --> 00:55:11.370 align:middle line:90%
And also 1 over a makes sense.

00:55:11.370 --> 00:55:15.210 align:middle line:84%
So we want to compare
this here with 1 over a.

00:55:15.210 --> 00:55:18.020 align:middle line:90%


00:55:18.020 --> 00:55:26.360 align:middle line:84%
And so this thing here is
1 over a n minus 1 over n

00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:30.110 align:middle line:84%
And now I can put it on
a common denominator.

00:55:30.110 --> 00:55:40.750 align:middle line:84%
So this is a minus a n divided
by a n times a so like that.

00:55:40.750 --> 00:55:42.080 align:middle line:90%
You can write it like this.

00:55:42.080 --> 00:55:45.640 align:middle line:84%
Now already the denominator
looks very promising

00:55:45.640 --> 00:55:48.655 align:middle line:84%
because we know
that this goes to 0.

00:55:48.655 --> 00:55:49.155 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:55:49.155 --> 00:55:53.500 align:middle line:90%


00:55:53.500 --> 00:55:55.970 align:middle line:90%
But now I need to bound this.

00:55:55.970 --> 00:55:59.070 align:middle line:90%
So I need to bound--

00:55:59.070 --> 00:55:59.570 align:middle line:90%
Right.

00:55:59.570 --> 00:56:00.500 align:middle line:90%
So I need to bound.

00:56:00.500 --> 00:56:02.470 align:middle line:90%
We need to bound.

00:56:02.470 --> 00:56:07.030 align:middle line:84%
So we want to bound this
here by epsilon when

00:56:07.030 --> 00:56:09.680 align:middle line:90%
little n is sufficiently large.

00:56:09.680 --> 00:56:13.070 align:middle line:84%
The top, the [? nominator ?]
here looks great.

00:56:13.070 --> 00:56:17.680 align:middle line:84%
The denominator maybe we're
a little bit worried about.

00:56:17.680 --> 00:56:19.460 align:middle line:90%
But the thing is that--

00:56:19.460 --> 00:56:33.620 align:middle line:84%
so we need to bound a n times
a, this here from below.

00:56:33.620 --> 00:56:36.830 align:middle line:84%
But we want to bound it
from below because then

00:56:36.830 --> 00:56:40.400 align:middle line:84%
when you're looking at 1 over
it, then that's an upper bound.

00:56:40.400 --> 00:56:44.720 align:middle line:84%
And really, because
a here is just

00:56:44.720 --> 00:56:50.160 align:middle line:84%
a fixed number that is not 0,
then it's equivalent to proving.

00:56:50.160 --> 00:57:05.080 align:middle line:84%
So this is equivalent to bound
the norm of a n from below.

00:57:05.080 --> 00:57:08.930 align:middle line:90%


00:57:08.930 --> 00:57:13.650 align:middle line:84%
Remember, we don't need to
bound it from below for all a n.

00:57:13.650 --> 00:57:20.550 align:middle line:84%
But we need to bounded from
below for n sufficiently large.

00:57:20.550 --> 00:57:25.440 align:middle line:84%
And so now, you make
the trivial observation.

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:35.140 align:middle line:84%
So that a n, you can write
a n as a n minus a plus a.

00:57:35.140 --> 00:57:39.970 align:middle line:84%
And so therefore,
therefore, the norm of a n

00:57:39.970 --> 00:57:46.710 align:middle line:84%
is bounded by the norm of a
n minus a plus the norm of a.

00:57:46.710 --> 00:57:52.210 align:middle line:90%


00:57:52.210 --> 00:57:55.855 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, this was not the--

00:57:55.855 --> 00:57:58.100 align:middle line:84%
this was not how I
wanted to write it.

00:57:58.100 --> 00:58:00.940 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to write it
slightly differently.

00:58:00.940 --> 00:58:03.790 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to write a.

00:58:03.790 --> 00:58:05.630 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to do the
symmetric thing.

00:58:05.630 --> 00:58:09.620 align:middle line:84%
But I'm doing it-- so I'm
writing a in as a minus--

00:58:09.620 --> 00:58:14.620 align:middle line:84%
so in writing a as a
minus a n plus a n.

00:58:14.620 --> 00:58:17.920 align:middle line:90%


00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:22.480 align:middle line:84%
And then, if I do
that, then I can just

00:58:22.480 --> 00:58:25.640 align:middle line:84%
take the absolute
value of a is bounded

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:28.700 align:middle line:84%
by the absolute value
of this difference

00:58:28.700 --> 00:58:33.890 align:middle line:90%
plus the absolute value of a n.

00:58:33.890 --> 00:58:37.800 align:middle line:84%
And now I can move this
here over on the other side.

00:58:37.800 --> 00:58:45.380 align:middle line:84%
So this here implies
that norm of a minus

00:58:45.380 --> 00:58:53.060 align:middle line:84%
the norm of a minus a n is
less or equal to this here.

00:58:53.060 --> 00:58:56.240 align:middle line:90%


00:58:56.240 --> 00:59:00.450 align:middle line:84%
And now, you see that
this thing here is--

00:59:00.450 --> 00:59:07.110 align:middle line:84%
so now we're going to use that
this here was not equal to 0.

00:59:07.110 --> 00:59:10.430 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
bounded away from 0.

00:59:10.430 --> 00:59:18.600 align:middle line:84%
And so now we can take,
say, a here over 2.

00:59:18.600 --> 00:59:21.560 align:middle line:90%
So we can use this here.

00:59:21.560 --> 00:59:25.310 align:middle line:90%
We can use norm of a over 2.

00:59:25.310 --> 00:59:28.750 align:middle line:84%
This is a positive number
because a was not 0.

00:59:28.750 --> 00:59:34.070 align:middle line:84%
And we can use this in the
definition of that a n--

00:59:34.070 --> 00:59:50.600 align:middle line:84%
so use this in the definition of
that a n converges to a, right?

00:59:50.600 --> 00:59:52.960 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
if you are-- this

00:59:52.960 --> 01:00:00.580 align:middle line:84%
means that there
exists a capital

01:00:00.580 --> 01:00:02.480 align:middle line:90%
N. Let's call it capital N1.

01:00:02.480 --> 01:00:05.540 align:middle line:84%
It's not the final N
that we want to use.

01:00:05.540 --> 01:00:09.850 align:middle line:84%
But there exists a capital N1
so that if little n is bigger

01:00:09.850 --> 01:00:16.720 align:middle line:84%
than this capital N1, then,
actually, we have that a n--

01:00:16.720 --> 01:00:23.065 align:middle line:84%
a minus a n is less
than this thing here.

01:00:23.065 --> 01:00:29.345 align:middle line:90%


01:00:29.345 --> 01:00:31.280 align:middle line:90%
But now, you see that--

01:00:31.280 --> 01:00:34.220 align:middle line:84%
this means that when you're
looking at-- when you go up

01:00:34.220 --> 01:00:36.890 align:middle line:90%
here, and you're looking at--

01:00:36.890 --> 01:00:39.870 align:middle line:84%
when you go up to
that line before--

01:00:39.870 --> 01:00:41.620 align:middle line:90%
so this is the line from before.

01:00:41.620 --> 01:00:45.890 align:middle line:90%


01:00:45.890 --> 01:00:46.610 align:middle line:90%
Sorry.

01:00:46.610 --> 01:00:50.480 align:middle line:84%
This is minus this
here-- this and this.

01:00:50.480 --> 01:00:55.020 align:middle line:84%
When you're looking at this line
here, well, this thing here--

01:00:55.020 --> 01:00:59.210 align:middle line:84%
this here is at
most half of this.

01:00:59.210 --> 01:01:08.771 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here is bigger
than this thing here over 2.

01:01:08.771 --> 01:01:14.871 align:middle line:84%
And so now you see that we have
bounded these guys from below.

01:01:14.871 --> 01:01:17.670 align:middle line:90%
And so now we go back up to--

01:01:17.670 --> 01:01:21.610 align:middle line:84%
so now we go back up to--
we're looking at C minus--

01:01:21.610 --> 01:01:22.370 align:middle line:90%
oh, sorry.

01:01:22.370 --> 01:01:26.715 align:middle line:84%
We're looking at
Cn minus 1 over a.

01:01:26.715 --> 01:01:29.418 align:middle line:90%


01:01:29.418 --> 01:01:34.960 align:middle line:90%
This is this up here.

01:01:34.960 --> 01:01:39.280 align:middle line:84%
I'm just transferring that
equation down to this board

01:01:39.280 --> 01:01:40.600 align:middle line:90%
here.

01:01:40.600 --> 01:01:48.020 align:middle line:84%
So this here is a n, a,
minus a n, divided by--

01:01:48.020 --> 01:01:50.620 align:middle line:84%
and I can just take the
absolute value separately

01:01:50.620 --> 01:01:55.905 align:middle line:84%
of the denominator-- and the
denominator, a n times a.

01:01:55.905 --> 01:01:58.600 align:middle line:90%


01:01:58.600 --> 01:01:59.560 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:01:59.560 --> 01:02:08.110 align:middle line:84%
So now you see that this thing
here, as long as-- so when

01:02:08.110 --> 01:02:13.540 align:middle line:84%
n here, little n, is bigger
than N1, well, then we have

01:02:13.540 --> 01:02:16.870 align:middle line:84%
that this thing here
is at the very least

01:02:16.870 --> 01:02:21.480 align:middle line:90%
the absolute value of a over 2.

01:02:21.480 --> 01:02:23.670 align:middle line:84%
So this means that
this thing here, we

01:02:23.670 --> 01:02:28.030 align:middle line:84%
can now bound from
above, like this.

01:02:28.030 --> 01:02:32.040 align:middle line:84%
This is as long as you
have this inequality here.

01:02:32.040 --> 01:02:36.730 align:middle line:84%
And this thing here--
this is just a norm of a.

01:02:36.730 --> 01:02:39.850 align:middle line:84%
This here will give you
another norm of a over 2.

01:02:39.850 --> 01:02:41.770 align:middle line:90%
So the 2 jumps up.

01:02:41.770 --> 01:02:43.265 align:middle line:90%
So it's like this thing here.

01:02:43.265 --> 01:02:49.804 align:middle line:90%


01:02:49.804 --> 01:02:53.370 align:middle line:90%
And now you see that--

01:02:53.370 --> 01:02:57.702 align:middle line:84%
now you see that this a
is just like a constant.

01:02:57.702 --> 01:03:02.530 align:middle line:84%
So this means that I may have
to go even further out than N1.

01:03:02.530 --> 01:03:04.830 align:middle line:84%
But if I go even
further out, then I

01:03:04.830 --> 01:03:09.435 align:middle line:84%
can make this thing here smaller
than a given epsilon, OK?

01:03:09.435 --> 01:03:12.762 align:middle line:90%


01:03:12.762 --> 01:03:13.780 align:middle line:90%
All right.

01:03:13.780 --> 01:03:15.580 align:middle line:84%
So this was like the
outline, if you will.

01:03:15.580 --> 01:03:21.180 align:middle line:84%
But that's not-- at this point,
that's not very much to fill in.

01:03:21.180 --> 01:03:21.680 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:03:21.680 --> 01:03:24.944 align:middle line:84%
So now I want to talk
about subsequences.

01:03:24.944 --> 01:03:38.410 align:middle line:90%


01:03:38.410 --> 01:03:40.750 align:middle line:90%
And then I want to--

01:03:40.750 --> 01:03:44.420 align:middle line:84%
then I want to prove a little
theorem about subsequences.

01:03:44.420 --> 01:04:00.370 align:middle line:90%


01:04:00.370 --> 01:04:03.940 align:middle line:90%
So I have a sequence.

01:04:03.940 --> 01:04:10.580 align:middle line:84%
And so I have a sequence
and then a subsequence.

01:04:10.580 --> 01:04:12.560 align:middle line:84%
So I'll give you
first some examples.

01:04:12.560 --> 01:04:15.030 align:middle line:90%
And then I will explain.

01:04:15.030 --> 01:04:17.520 align:middle line:84%
Then I will give you
the proper definition

01:04:17.520 --> 01:04:21.880 align:middle line:90%
of what a subsequence is.

01:04:21.880 --> 01:04:28.870 align:middle line:84%
So I'll start with this
sequence from before.

01:04:28.870 --> 01:04:33.690 align:middle line:84%
So this was the sequence where
a1 was minus 1, a2 was 1,

01:04:33.690 --> 01:04:35.740 align:middle line:90%
a3 was minus 1.

01:04:35.740 --> 01:04:40.770 align:middle line:84%
It was alternating
between minus 1 and 1.

01:04:40.770 --> 01:04:43.770 align:middle line:90%
And so, in this case here--

01:04:43.770 --> 01:04:49.950 align:middle line:84%
in this case here, if
you take the sequence--

01:04:49.950 --> 01:04:57.180 align:middle line:90%
let's call it-- let's call it b.

01:04:57.180 --> 01:05:01.030 align:middle line:84%
Let's call it-- let's
use a different index.

01:05:01.030 --> 01:05:01.985 align:middle line:90%
Let's call it bk.

01:05:01.985 --> 01:05:04.590 align:middle line:90%


01:05:04.590 --> 01:05:07.030 align:middle line:84%
So k here plays the
same role as n before.

01:05:07.030 --> 01:05:10.440 align:middle line:84%
But I want to use a different
symbol to not somehow confuse

01:05:10.440 --> 01:05:13.060 align:middle line:90%
with the n over here.

01:05:13.060 --> 01:05:15.230 align:middle line:90%
So if I take--

01:05:15.230 --> 01:05:19.720 align:middle line:84%
so I could take a sequence
that was like 1 all the time,

01:05:19.720 --> 01:05:20.990 align:middle line:90%
this here, for all k.

01:05:20.990 --> 01:05:23.920 align:middle line:90%


01:05:23.920 --> 01:05:26.390 align:middle line:84%
This here would
be a subsequence.

01:05:26.390 --> 01:05:28.210 align:middle line:84%
This would correspond
to that you

01:05:28.210 --> 01:05:35.030 align:middle line:84%
took all the even ones, that
you just take all the even ones.

01:05:35.030 --> 01:05:37.780 align:middle line:90%
So this is like a subsequence.

01:05:37.780 --> 01:05:40.550 align:middle line:84%
You could also have
another example.

01:05:40.550 --> 01:05:43.150 align:middle line:90%
So this is example 1.

01:05:43.150 --> 01:05:47.580 align:middle line:84%
Another example is where
you took all the odd ones.

01:05:47.580 --> 01:05:50.260 align:middle line:90%


01:05:50.260 --> 01:05:55.450 align:middle line:84%
So this here is
also a subsequence.

01:05:55.450 --> 01:06:00.190 align:middle line:84%
And you could do something more
elaborate, where you take--

01:06:00.190 --> 01:06:05.050 align:middle line:84%
say, first, you take
the first two odd,

01:06:05.050 --> 01:06:09.160 align:middle line:84%
and then you take
the next two even.

01:06:09.160 --> 01:06:11.440 align:middle line:84%
So you could have
a sequence that was

01:06:11.440 --> 01:06:14.980 align:middle line:90%
like b1 is equal to minus 1.

01:06:14.980 --> 01:06:19.440 align:middle line:90%
b2 is equal to minus 1.

01:06:19.440 --> 01:06:25.540 align:middle line:84%
b3-- now it becomes
the next two even ones.

01:06:25.540 --> 01:06:29.650 align:middle line:84%
And then you go back to the
next two odd ones, et cetera.

01:06:29.650 --> 01:06:32.656 align:middle line:84%
That would be
another subsequence.

01:06:32.656 --> 01:06:36.840 align:middle line:90%


01:06:36.840 --> 01:06:38.863 align:middle line:84%
Let me look at a
few more examples.

01:06:38.863 --> 01:06:49.350 align:middle line:90%


01:06:49.350 --> 01:06:53.760 align:middle line:84%
So, for instance,
if your sequence,

01:06:53.760 --> 01:06:55.920 align:middle line:90%
your original sequence--

01:06:55.920 --> 01:06:58.980 align:middle line:90%
so here's another example.

01:06:58.980 --> 01:07:07.470 align:middle line:84%
If your original sequence was
just that a n was equal to n,

01:07:07.470 --> 01:07:10.820 align:middle line:90%
then you could take a sequence.

01:07:10.820 --> 01:07:17.110 align:middle line:84%
So then the sequence where
you just take the odd numbers,

01:07:17.110 --> 01:07:19.220 align:middle line:90%
this here is a subsequence.

01:07:19.220 --> 01:07:23.200 align:middle line:90%


01:07:23.200 --> 01:07:28.840 align:middle line:84%
And likewise, if you take
just the even numbers,

01:07:28.840 --> 01:07:33.500 align:middle line:84%
this is also a
sequence, a subsequence.

01:07:33.500 --> 01:07:38.160 align:middle line:90%


01:07:38.160 --> 01:07:40.270 align:middle line:90%
But if you're looking at--

01:07:40.270 --> 01:07:45.470 align:middle line:84%
if you look at, say, something
like this, where you're taking--

01:07:45.470 --> 01:07:50.834 align:middle line:84%
so if you define a sequence
where it was 1, 1--

01:07:50.834 --> 01:07:53.770 align:middle line:90%


01:07:53.770 --> 01:07:56.523 align:middle line:90%
1, 1, 2, even like this--

01:07:56.523 --> 01:08:00.850 align:middle line:90%


01:08:00.850 --> 01:08:02.990 align:middle line:90%
this here is not a subsequence.

01:08:02.990 --> 01:08:12.030 align:middle line:84%
This is not a subsequence,
because you have--

01:08:12.030 --> 01:08:15.930 align:middle line:84%
what you have done here is that
you have taken the same number

01:08:15.930 --> 01:08:17.140 align:middle line:90%
several times.

01:08:17.140 --> 01:08:18.880 align:middle line:84%
And it doesn't
appear several times.

01:08:18.880 --> 01:08:22.080 align:middle line:84%
The value doesn't appear several
times in the original one.

01:08:22.080 --> 01:08:24.450 align:middle line:90%
So that's not allowed.

01:08:24.450 --> 01:08:28.930 align:middle line:84%
It's also not allowed to
do something like this.

01:08:28.930 --> 01:08:32.470 align:middle line:84%
This here is also not
a-- so not a subsequence,

01:08:32.470 --> 01:08:35.490 align:middle line:84%
another thing that's
not a subsequence--

01:08:35.490 --> 01:08:37.750 align:middle line:84%
when you take
things out of order.

01:08:37.750 --> 01:08:42.640 align:middle line:84%
So if this here was
the original sequence,

01:08:42.640 --> 01:08:48.540 align:middle line:84%
if you're now looking at
a sequence that was 3, 2,

01:08:48.540 --> 01:08:52.710 align:middle line:84%
and then 4, 5, this
here is-- et cetera--

01:08:52.710 --> 01:08:55.710 align:middle line:84%
this here is not a
subsequence either,

01:08:55.710 --> 01:08:59.819 align:middle line:84%
because things are
taken out of order.

01:08:59.819 --> 01:09:03.346 align:middle line:84%
So now, what is the formal
definition of a subsequence?

01:09:03.346 --> 01:09:05.880 align:middle line:90%


01:09:05.880 --> 01:09:07.906 align:middle line:90%
So here is a formal definition.

01:09:07.906 --> 01:09:30.100 align:middle line:90%


01:09:30.100 --> 01:09:33.669 align:middle line:90%
So you have a sequence, a n.

01:09:33.669 --> 01:09:49.210 align:middle line:84%
A subsequence of a n is where
you have a map, g, from N

01:09:49.210 --> 01:09:53.890 align:middle line:84%
into N. This is
an increasing map.

01:09:53.890 --> 01:09:55.520 align:middle line:90%
This is strictly increasing.

01:09:55.520 --> 01:10:02.920 align:middle line:90%


01:10:02.920 --> 01:10:06.780 align:middle line:84%
And then, if you're thinking
about this thing here,

01:10:06.780 --> 01:10:10.950 align:middle line:84%
you think about this
as a function, f,

01:10:10.950 --> 01:10:15.450 align:middle line:84%
then you now could think about
the composition of these two

01:10:15.450 --> 01:10:19.380 align:middle line:90%
functions, so this thing here.

01:10:19.380 --> 01:10:22.950 align:middle line:84%
And maybe I will use
a different notation

01:10:22.950 --> 01:10:27.070 align:middle line:84%
like this, a different
index like this.

01:10:27.070 --> 01:10:34.170 align:middle line:84%
This thing here, bk, this
here is a subsequence.

01:10:34.170 --> 01:10:38.470 align:middle line:84%
So you see that this
here, when you pick--

01:10:38.470 --> 01:10:42.870 align:middle line:84%
if you have a
sequence like this,

01:10:42.870 --> 01:10:46.750 align:middle line:84%
the first one could be
anything in the original one.

01:10:46.750 --> 01:10:50.400 align:middle line:84%
But once you have fixed the
first one, you can't look back,

01:10:50.400 --> 01:10:52.170 align:middle line:90%
or you can't go to this.

01:10:52.170 --> 01:10:55.740 align:middle line:84%
You have to-- the next element
have to be somewhat further

01:10:55.740 --> 01:10:57.427 align:middle line:90%
out in the sequence.

01:10:57.427 --> 01:11:01.682 align:middle line:90%
And that continues.

01:11:01.682 --> 01:11:05.660 align:middle line:84%
And this here is often
just to indicate that it's

01:11:05.660 --> 01:11:07.980 align:middle line:90%
a subsequence of this sequence.

01:11:07.980 --> 01:11:15.440 align:middle line:84%
Then the standard notation is
a n and then another subscript.

01:11:15.440 --> 01:11:17.930 align:middle line:84%
So anyway, so of
course, hopefully,

01:11:17.930 --> 01:11:20.480 align:middle line:84%
there's not too many
subsequences of sequences,

01:11:20.480 --> 01:11:25.730 align:middle line:84%
because each time, it's supposed
to be another subscript.

01:11:25.730 --> 01:11:28.250 align:middle line:84%
Now, there's a little
theorem that we can just

01:11:28.250 --> 01:11:30.140 align:middle line:90%
prove here at the end.

01:11:30.140 --> 01:11:34.130 align:middle line:84%
And that is that
if you-- and it's--

01:11:34.130 --> 01:11:38.940 align:middle line:84%
yeah, it's sometimes--
it's a very simple fact.

01:11:38.940 --> 01:11:43.280 align:middle line:84%
But it is sometimes
a useful fact.

01:11:43.280 --> 01:11:48.300 align:middle line:84%
And that is that if
you take a sequence--

01:11:48.300 --> 01:11:58.280 align:middle line:84%
so a sequence--
so theorem, that--

01:11:58.280 --> 01:12:11.340 align:middle line:84%
so a sequence, a n, is
convergent to a if and only

01:12:11.340 --> 01:12:37.380 align:middle line:84%
if all subsequences
of a n converge to a.

01:12:37.380 --> 01:12:38.140 align:middle line:90%
OK.

01:12:38.140 --> 01:12:43.500 align:middle line:84%
Now, to prove this, there's
two things we need to prove,

01:12:43.500 --> 01:12:46.720 align:middle line:84%
because it's an "if
and only if" statement.

01:12:46.720 --> 01:12:49.930 align:middle line:84%
So we need to prove that
if it is convergent,

01:12:49.930 --> 01:12:52.870 align:middle line:84%
then all subsequences
are also convergent.

01:12:52.870 --> 01:12:55.890 align:middle line:84%
And then we need to prove
that if all subsequences are

01:12:55.890 --> 01:12:59.080 align:middle line:84%
convergent, then the original
sequence is convergent.

01:12:59.080 --> 01:13:01.800 align:middle line:84%
But one of the two
implications is trivial.

01:13:01.800 --> 01:13:13.960 align:middle line:84%
So one of the two
implications is trivial.

01:13:13.960 --> 01:13:16.880 align:middle line:90%


01:13:16.880 --> 01:13:25.940 align:middle line:84%
And that is that,
namely, since--

01:13:25.940 --> 01:13:30.920 align:middle line:84%
so the map-- remember that the
map to define a subsequence

01:13:30.920 --> 01:13:34.620 align:middle line:90%
has to be strictly increasing.

01:13:34.620 --> 01:13:42.470 align:middle line:84%
So remember that a sequence
was a function like this.

01:13:42.470 --> 01:13:44.280 align:middle line:90%
That was a sequence.

01:13:44.280 --> 01:13:47.600 align:middle line:84%
And a subsequence-- there,
you have another map

01:13:47.600 --> 01:13:50.600 align:middle line:90%
that is strictly increasing.

01:13:50.600 --> 01:13:53.100 align:middle line:84%
And then you're looking
at the composition.

01:13:53.100 --> 01:13:57.440 align:middle line:84%
But if you take this other
map to be the identity,

01:13:57.440 --> 01:14:03.250 align:middle line:84%
that the other map is like g
of k is equal to k, of course,

01:14:03.250 --> 01:14:05.130 align:middle line:90%
this is strictly increasing.

01:14:05.130 --> 01:14:09.810 align:middle line:84%
And if you did-- if this here
map was the identity, then

01:14:09.810 --> 01:14:14.004 align:middle line:84%
the subsequence would just
be the original sequence.

01:14:14.004 --> 01:14:16.980 align:middle line:84%
So one of the two
implications here

01:14:16.980 --> 01:14:27.400 align:middle line:84%
is trivial, since a n itself
is admittedly trivial.

01:14:27.400 --> 01:14:28.900 align:middle line:90%
But it is a subsequence.

01:14:28.900 --> 01:14:35.860 align:middle line:90%


01:14:35.860 --> 01:14:41.280 align:middle line:84%
So if all subsequences
converge to a, well, then

01:14:41.280 --> 01:14:45.610 align:middle line:84%
the original sequence,
since it is a subsequence,

01:14:45.610 --> 01:14:47.250 align:middle line:90%
certainly, it will converge.

01:14:47.250 --> 01:14:49.050 align:middle line:90%
So that was trivial.

01:14:49.050 --> 01:14:54.780 align:middle line:84%
OK, so we just need to prove
that if a n converged to a, then

01:14:54.780 --> 01:14:57.230 align:middle line:90%
any subsequence.

01:14:57.230 --> 01:15:02.900 align:middle line:84%
But this is not much more
difficult, because you see,

01:15:02.900 --> 01:15:07.310 align:middle line:84%
if you're-- so
given an epsilon--

01:15:07.310 --> 01:15:08.945 align:middle line:90%
so now, given epsilon--

01:15:08.945 --> 01:15:12.260 align:middle line:90%


01:15:12.260 --> 01:15:21.335 align:middle line:84%
so now we have-- so we now
have that a n converges to a.

01:15:21.335 --> 01:15:24.960 align:middle line:84%
And we're looking at
a subsequence, ank.

01:15:24.960 --> 01:15:35.180 align:middle line:84%
And we want to show that
ank also converges to a.

01:15:35.180 --> 01:15:41.540 align:middle line:84%
So given epsilon, given
epsilon greater than 0,

01:15:41.540 --> 01:15:51.590 align:middle line:84%
there exists a capital N so
that if little n is bigger

01:15:51.590 --> 01:15:57.960 align:middle line:84%
than capital N, then a n
minus a is less than epsilon.

01:15:57.960 --> 01:16:06.030 align:middle line:84%
But now you see that if k
is bigger than capital N,

01:16:06.030 --> 01:16:10.740 align:middle line:90%
then what corresponds to--

01:16:10.740 --> 01:16:17.730 align:middle line:84%
this here is-- this here, how to
think about it-- this here, nk,

01:16:17.730 --> 01:16:20.520 align:middle line:84%
you should really think
about that this thing here

01:16:20.520 --> 01:16:24.742 align:middle line:84%
is the value of this
strictly increasing function.

01:16:24.742 --> 01:16:26.700 align:middle line:90%
But this thing here is--

01:16:26.700 --> 01:16:30.240 align:middle line:84%
because it's strictly
increasing, it's bigger than k.

01:16:30.240 --> 01:16:35.080 align:middle line:84%
So you see that if this thing
here is bigger than this,

01:16:35.080 --> 01:16:38.910 align:middle line:84%
then means that this index
here is further out than,

01:16:38.910 --> 01:16:43.860 align:middle line:84%
in particular, the
capital N. And so this

01:16:43.860 --> 01:16:47.880 align:middle line:84%
means that if you have
this here, then ank,

01:16:47.880 --> 01:16:51.310 align:middle line:90%
this is some element like this.

01:16:51.310 --> 01:16:54.810 align:middle line:84%
But it's further
out than capital N.

01:16:54.810 --> 01:16:57.770 align:middle line:84%
So this thing here
surely will also

01:16:57.770 --> 01:17:02.180 align:middle line:84%
be less than epsilon because
it's falling under here.

01:17:02.180 --> 01:17:09.450 align:middle line:84%
So that implication
wasn't too much harder.

01:17:09.450 --> 01:17:12.904 align:middle line:84%
And that's sometimes
useful, that--

01:17:12.904 --> 01:17:19.370 align:middle line:84%
so if-- yeah, it's sometimes
useful that you're looking

01:17:19.370 --> 01:17:28.238 align:middle line:84%
at a sequence, and you see that
if it is converging, then--

01:17:28.238 --> 01:17:29.780 align:middle line:84%
you're looking at
a sequence, and you

01:17:29.780 --> 01:17:32.670 align:middle line:84%
see that there's a subsequence
that is not converging,

01:17:32.670 --> 01:17:36.140 align:middle line:84%
or you have that there are
two different subsequences

01:17:36.140 --> 01:17:39.440 align:middle line:84%
of a given sequence that
converge to different limits.

01:17:39.440 --> 01:17:42.780 align:middle line:84%
Then the original sequence
wasn't converging either.

01:17:42.780 --> 01:17:43.850 align:middle line:90%
Yeah?

01:17:43.850 --> 01:17:46.310 align:middle line:84%
AUDIENCE: Can you not
have a finite subsequence

01:17:46.310 --> 01:17:49.910 align:middle line:84%
of-- a convergent subsequence
that doesn't get to n,

01:17:49.910 --> 01:17:54.700 align:middle line:84%
so it hasn't arrived at
the point of convergence?

01:17:54.700 --> 01:17:56.460 align:middle line:84%
TOBIAS COLDING: So
convergence is always

01:17:56.460 --> 01:18:00.310 align:middle line:84%
something about the tail,
about the end, right?

01:18:00.310 --> 01:18:05.282 align:middle line:84%
It never cares about what
happened in the beginning.

01:18:05.282 --> 01:18:08.070 align:middle line:84%
So there might be
finitely many n's

01:18:08.070 --> 01:18:11.890 align:middle line:84%
initially where
things are crazy,

01:18:11.890 --> 01:18:13.948 align:middle line:90%
but then from there on out.

01:18:13.948 --> 01:18:14.490 align:middle line:90%
AUDIENCE: OK.

01:18:14.490 --> 01:18:16.800 align:middle line:84%
The subsequences that we
care about in this case

01:18:16.800 --> 01:18:18.900 align:middle line:84%
are those subsequences
that also--

01:18:18.900 --> 01:18:20.025 align:middle line:90%
TOBIAS COLDING: Yeah, yeah.

01:18:20.025 --> 01:18:22.200 align:middle line:84%
So all sequences,
including subsequences,

01:18:22.200 --> 01:18:24.730 align:middle line:90%
are infinite things, right?

01:18:24.730 --> 01:18:25.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:18:25.350 --> 01:18:28.590 align:middle line:84%
So like-- that's right,
because the thing is

01:18:28.590 --> 01:18:32.820 align:middle line:90%
that you had to have this map.

01:18:32.820 --> 01:18:34.000 align:middle line:90%
Maybe I erased it.

01:18:34.000 --> 01:18:40.270 align:middle line:84%
But g here had to be a map from
all the natural numbers N to N.

01:18:40.270 --> 01:18:44.950 align:middle line:84%
So it means that for each
element here, you get something.

01:18:44.950 --> 01:18:46.930 align:middle line:84%
So there's really
infinitely many of them.

01:18:46.930 --> 01:18:48.480 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

01:18:48.480 --> 01:18:52.000 align:middle line:90%